ates USA USA USA USA USA United States of America WTO WTO WTO WTO WTO World Trade Organization 7 I. Introduction Among the world\u2019s regions, Asia-Pacific is well-known as one in which many societies are managing to find ways to escape from poverty and underdevelopment. The paths out of deprivation have varied among countries; societies in the region employed a variety of political arrangements after starting off with dissimilar social and physical endowments. Moreover, within the experience of each country, development strategies often were revised in response to the changing global environment and the achieved level of development. Despite the success stories in East Asia, the human development challenge in Asia- Pacific remains as daunting as at the beginning of the 20th Century. In 2001, 431 million people in South Asia (31 percent of the population) and 271 million in East Asia (15 percent of the population) lived on less than US$1 a day (UN Millennium Project 2004). Levels of development range widely, with the richest society in the region enjoying a per-capita income more than 100 times that of the poorest. Of great consequence is that within many countries, extreme contrasts continue to exist in access to decent livelihoods, human dignity, and a meaningful role in society. Trade has always been a key part of Asia Pacific development strategies. In developmental terms, the trade strategies of successful countries in the region have been applied to move an economy up the ladder in the international division of labour. These will always involve, whether or not gains are shared equitably, raising productivity of numerous factors. Hypothetically, an economy could move up the ladder without undertaking human development. This might involve severe exploitation of the factors of production by a few. It also would be easy to imagine \u2013 as has indeed taken place \u2013 that this pattern of development would reach an upper bound, such as when non-renewable resources are exhausted (Diamond 2005).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6b69e407-1e6d-4e10-9128-ef7e3687ad2a": {"__data__": {"id_": "6b69e407-1e6d-4e10-9128-ef7e3687ad2a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9ed862f023e3bd1c8171b86aac2abe0499a25c01969dbe8cf458c831ac59fd54"}, "2": {"node_id": "ce4b115d-f6a0-40a1-87b5-746a2eaf9557", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "51d7403471ef753d10659f81c00e988f3bd7365821c54d84a95b8287115e3be2"}}, "hash": "30f5e7b24e0ab32039b8e36a51d542b3043b6034313f64fdfcdca25946f46116", "text": "8 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific In the second half of the 20th Century, successful countries in Asia- Pacific undertook a pattern of trade expansion that, even with clear faults, went hand-in-hand with human development; for the most part, trade and human development reinforced each other. These actual experiences assist us in understanding the human development impact of trade and trade reforms, whether at the domestic or international level. In particular, East Asian economies established the key role that external trade can play to raise the productivity of their people and to steadily absorb the unemployed and underemployed into higher-paying work (Bhagwati 2004). This", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7eb4268e-769b-47b1-8240-77e4d09e3cd5": {"__data__": {"id_": "7eb4268e-769b-47b1-8240-77e4d09e3cd5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "393a2bed7ac69c74b7799addc2adc966950347e6f2a55f680f7933360aedf0a7"}}, "hash": "393a2bed7ac69c74b7799addc2adc966950347e6f2a55f680f7933360aedf0a7", "text": "was achieved through a dynamic private-public sector partnership that ensured that foreign exchange earnings would be invested back into enterprises and used to import critical inputs and technology (Aky\u00fcz and Gore 2002; Chang 1994; Rodrik 1995), as well as by making sure that workers shared in the benefits of growth through increased social protection and higher pay (UNRISD 2005, Amsden and Chu 2003). Through this process, countries fashioned their international competitive advantages instead of passively depending upon inherited comparative advantages. Within a framework that sees external trade as the means by which countries alter their place in the international division of labour, high levels of human development tend to have a positive relationship with the country\u2019s effort to move up the development ladder and its international competitiveness. Societies can raise their level of human development in one of two ways: firstly, by pursuing economic growth as the top priority, under the presumption that growth will eventually translate into higher human development (and enhanced international competitiveness). Or they can devote their resources to directly raise human development even at the expense of growth, hoping that higher capabilities will lead to economic growth. We now need to more directly explore the connection between human development and trade. Trade has both direct impacts on human 9 development variables and impacts that are mediated through other variables. Economic growth is a key mediating1 variable. The analytical connection between human development and economic growth is well-trodden. A recent, and important, application is found in Ranis and Stewart (2005), drawing on a series of their own previous studies. Ranis and Stewart trace two alternative channels, one from economic growth to human development and the other from human development to economic growth. They differentiate between countries that follow a reasonably balanced path and those that follow \u201clopsided\u201d strategies that prioritise economic growth over human development or vice versa. They find, first of all, that neither lopsided strategy is sustainable. For example, \u201chuman development first\u201d strategies can run into fiscal constraints and balance of payments crises, while \u201ceconomic growth first\u201d strategies can reach limits of domestic supply of skilled labour and political instability. Secondly, however, they find that countries that overextend themselves in human development have a much better chance of weathering economic crises and resuming economic growth. Much has been made of the contrast between the development experiences of East Asia and South Asia. In human development terms, the contrast can be overdrawn, since both experiences demonstrate \u201chow favorable human development achievements \u2013 literacy, long, healthy lives of citizens, equitable distribution of assets, good public service, etc. \u2013 can provide suitable preconditions for economic growth, and how economic growth can in turn contribute to enhancing human development achievements further\u201d(Wagle 2003). While East Asia started with a considerably more favourable human development stock, 1 One important viewpoint is that economic growth is itself a key causative variable to successful expansion of external trade and international integration. If this is indeed the case, Rodrik suggests that international trade rules should not undermine the potential of developing countries to promote growth and utilise their policy space to do so (Rodrik 2001). 10 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific subsequent advances in human development endowment in India permitted modest liberalisation reforms in the early 1980s and technology-driven international integration in the late 1990s to materialise as faster economic growth. That human development is the goal of all conscious efforts at social change and economic development is the analytical starting point of this review of Asia Pacific trade policy. Economic development has been a contributing factor to human development, even though the input has often been secured through socially painful efforts to secure human rights. Economic development generates the means to support expanded material well-being and freedom of choice. The manner by which the additional material means is generated and distributed in the course of development determines, to a great extent, how economic progress promotes human development. Historically, increased commerce between societies has gone hand-in-hand with economic development. What we consider in this volume are two intimately conjoined issues as it relates to the Asia-Pacific experience: \ufffd The role trade has played in the material progress of societies in the region; and \ufffd The way in which human development is being promoted or diminished, or has languished, from interaction between trade and economic growth These two aspects are intimately related because of our particular view of what constitutes human development. 11 II. Asia\u2019s Trade Secret: Investing in People Human development is an expansive view of individual and social progress. To put some structure in the conception, the various", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "51692bb0-3ec6-467b-b6c6-3c49524acd6f": {"__data__": {"id_": "51692bb0-3ec6-467b-b6c6-3c49524acd6f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5b718067215e8c9965b373f5f1af22537040edc3a79ac8838d9d179fc1bbde6c"}, "3": {"node_id": "8e7e519e-ea0f-4bab-bbc0-918d380aded3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "28b0fc5c0d173484abe78b52a5a3f19ec7bff2375f7bfb05828a76c4c68b9816"}}, "hash": "005d2d8e801af72e826af6c6ced9542735c3ddb626838e41d30f7b3a4bd9cfa3", "text": "elements of human development can be grouped into four facets2: Empowerment Empowerment Empowerment Empowerment Empowerment Empowerment speaks to the capability of members of society to shape the processes and events that affect their lives. Historically, industrialisation begat urbanisation and the creation of a working class composed of individuals drawing income from their factory employment independent of patronage from the elite. This facilitated the emergence of an independent electorate in Western countries (Reinert 2005). In the 1960s and 1970s, East Asia\u2019s export drive relied heavily on mobilisation of female labour. For the women directly involved, the human development impact involved both gains and losses. In earning their own income independent of their families, many obtained greater personal freedom (Beneria 2003; Bhagwati 2004). However, because women were particularly important as a low-cost pool of labour for production in competitive export markets, enormous pressures have emerged to restrict the ability of these workers to participate in decisions on their working conditions (Beneria 2003; World Commission on the Social Dimension of Globalization 2004). Women\u2019s responsibilities as caregivers, as stipulated by social norms, also have restricted women\u2019s participation in determining working conditions, since many can work work only part-time3. A human development approach evaluates both the costs and benefits of trade in terms of empowerment and promotes the search for trade strategies that minimise the costs and maximise the benefits (Fontana, Joekes, Masika 1998). 2 See UNDP Asia Trade Initiative (2003). 3 In many societies, even if women work full-time, they are often not perceived as serious professionals since their primary role is considered as a caregiver. 12 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific Productivity Productivity Productivity Productivity Productivity Productivity involves the raising of human capabilities among members of society, both as an end in itself and as a means to raise the capability of society as a whole. This definition of productivity goes beyond the conventional one, which is usually reflected in declining required labour inputs or increasing outputs and which views the concept of productivity only as an end. In this view, productivity is also taken as a means. Productivity involves advances in health, education, and labour force capabilities. This requires two things (Islam 2001, p. 7): First, increasing incomes and protection from income volatility so that households can provide for the basic needs, such as nutrition, that are most efficiently provided within the household; second, robust markets and public institutions to provide those other basic needs, such as health and education, that cannot be provided by individual households. It is important to expand upon the crucial relationship between productivity and employment as key drivers to growth and development. In efforts to raise productivity, we must keep in mind that productivity increases are necessary but not sufficient for human development. It is possible to raise productivity, especially in the short- to medium-term, through declines in employment, in which case a single-minded effort to raise productivity has an adverse effect on employment and human development. Industrial development, buttressed by social programmes in health and education, played a critical role in raising productivity in the now- advanced countries4 (Reinert 2003b, p. 470-473; UNRISD 2005). For the latecomers in industrialisation, capital and technology imports are 4 Reinert (2003b) argues that, historically, economic development is activity-specific \u2013 i.e., it requires certain economic activities (Schumpeterian activities, as he calls them) that will raise the standard of living with better health and educational opportunities. UNRISD (2005) in country case studies underlines the role of social policies in the context of economic development in Asia. Kwon in UNRISD 2005, p.5, argues that economic development requires social policy. 13 critical to raising productivity (Chang 1994; Amsden 2001). By providing the foreign exchange and access to capital imports and technology, trade played a critical role in the success of newly industrialising countries in East Asia. While aggressively taking advantage of their lower wage costs to export less advanced goods, these countries consciously restructured and upgraded to higher technology and higher price goods and steadily broke out of their reliance on exporting commodities and cheap manufactures. This experience contrasts sharply with the colonial experience of many countries, which was characterised by continued low productivity exports on the part of the poorer country. The East Asia experience illustrates that a human development approach to trade is acutely sensitive to the questions of whether national and global trade policies are productivity-enhancing or -diminishing.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8e7e519e-ea0f-4bab-bbc0-918d380aded3": {"__data__": {"id_": "8e7e519e-ea0f-4bab-bbc0-918d380aded3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5b718067215e8c9965b373f5f1af22537040edc3a79ac8838d9d179fc1bbde6c"}, "2": {"node_id": "51692bb0-3ec6-467b-b6c6-3c49524acd6f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "005d2d8e801af72e826af6c6ced9542735c3ddb626838e41d30f7b3a4bd9cfa3"}}, "hash": "28b0fc5c0d173484abe78b52a5a3f19ec7bff2375f7bfb05828a76c4c68b9816", "text": "Equity Equity Equity Equity Equity Equity demands the progressive equalisation of access to opportunity for all members of society. It requires the dismantling of discriminatory rules and unfair economic processes that disadvantage certain sub-groups in society. Attention to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "66a03c34-fcc9-43ea-a0a3-87f884e7da33": {"__data__": {"id_": "66a03c34-fcc9-43ea-a0a3-87f884e7da33", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "127a713403bd71b829b7490b9d45d7f5c316d17f132ea15364070772f9e91e9b"}}, "hash": "127a713403bd71b829b7490b9d45d7f5c316d17f132ea15364070772f9e91e9b", "text": "equity considerations, such as the implementation of land reform at an early stage, has generally been associated with successful economies in East Asia. Highly unequal asset ownership, both in terms of physical and human assets, generally implies a limited social capacity for \u201ctrickle down,\u201d i.e., benefits from economic growth are unable to be shared widely and represent an obstacle to a more general advance in productivity in society. Expanded trade creates larger markets and new opportunities for income and employment. Markets by themselves rely solely on price-cost considerations and are unable to address issues of equity. One key channel of impact that trade has on equity is through its differential impact on different production sectors and on different capacities of labour. The intensification of world trade has generally been associated with skill-biased technical change (SBTC), benefiting, in terms of higher pay, skilled workers versus the unskilled, and in terms of higher margins 14 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific over cost in more technologically advanced products. These influences have tended to exacerbate inequalities in place before trade expansion. A human development approach to trade recognises that trade by itself cannot address existing or induced inequities and promotes the search for complementary policies. Sustainability Sustainability Sustainability Sustainability Sustainability Sustainability is concerned with the durability of social gains and that these gains do not prevent subsequent generations from improving their own welfare. Environmental concerns are a part of sustainability, but equally important are concerns about human capabilities, such as health and education. Sustainability also concerns financial stability, political stability and social progress. Financial crises that undermine previous gains in growth belie sustainability. Sustainability also draws our attention to episodes of retreat from already achieved progress. Various indicators of health of a population, such as life expectancy at birth, maternal mortality, and the mortality of children younger than 5, are robust indicators of social gains because these embody longer-term processes over the whole population. Changes in the rate of improvement in these indicators are unmistakable signs of social progress or regress, or of catastrophes such as the outbreak of war, social unrest or, as in the case of most economies in the Eastern Europe, dislocations as a result of haphazard economic reform. Changes in the rates of improvements in these statistics are therefore early indicators of sustainability. These measures also embody the incidence of disparities in society; a society whose high average income is distributed unequally would tend to show poor performance on these indicators. The indicators reflect the sum total of the capabilities of individual households and of society. A key channel by which trade affects human development is through these changes in capabilities. When trade outcomes have considerable impact on livelihoods and income, then they can have a profound effect on household capability. When imports of 15 agricultural commodities, subsidised by industrial economies, threaten the livelihood of farmers, then these capabilities are undermined and sustainability is threatened. Trade rules also can affect a government\u2019s capability to provide health and manage domestic conflict. Asia-Pacific countries have not relied heavily on social welfare systems to provide social benefits, but have instead depended on steady growth and employment and on labour regulations in the public and private sectors5. Especially in Asia-Pacific, a human development approach to trade must pay particular attention to the impact of trade on growth, employment and livelihood, because in this region these are the key contributors to sustainability. Three other considerations apply to each of these aspects on human development. First, in the trade area, these four aspects interact closely. For example, empowering women working in export industries to improve their working conditions helps to promote equity. Workers enjoying better working conditions can in turn engage in greater self- investment to improve their productivity. In more successful exporting countries, such as the Republic of Korea, companies responded to pressure from increased labour costs by boosting labour productivity through investments in capital goods. Thus, at the level of society, equity can in turn engender productivity and sustainability. In the textile and clothing sector, efforts to improve cost competitiveness also could involve shifting the product mix, such as reducing reliance on low- quality exports. Second, that changing economic environments, including those brought about by the outcomes in global trade negotiations and unilateral actions by other countries, continually confront the way trade promotes human development. The inclusion of intellectual property protections in the 5 Not all labour protections have to be imposed through Government regulations. During its growth phase, Japan\u2019s leading companies set for themselves the standard of lifetime employment, an adaptation of older forms of labour relations. 16", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a770aeb0-7d8c-4308-aa94-f9b2e83899be": {"__data__": {"id_": "a770aeb0-7d8c-4308-aa94-f9b2e83899be", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9b775eba219f99370094c7fc4e2eb5d2f0cee710135320ef7c64021b13831734"}}, "hash": "9b775eba219f99370094c7fc4e2eb5d2f0cee710135320ef7c64021b13831734", "text": "| People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific World Trade Organization regime has raised the cost of drugs in health systems in many developing countries. Third, what is required is a progressive realisation of these goals, not immediate achievement. Changes in trade outcomes and rules therefore can be evaluated on whether, in the first place, these changes risk a retreat from gains already achieved. If human development is the goal, our framework is skeptical about so-called tradeoffs in development policy. Changes in trade outcomes need to be evaluated on the extent to which they promote one aspect at the expense of others, with the recognition that such tradeoffs generally represent a diminution of the whole. These basic elements of human development now provide the basis by which we can outline the different channels by which trade affects human development and, in turn, human development affects trade. 17 III. Trade Policy and the Millenium Development Goals (MDGs) As a practical plan to achieve the cumulated obligations assumed by Governments in the series of United Nations-sponsored World Summits since the 1980s, UN member countries declared their commitment to the Millennium Development Goals in September 2000. MDGs provide specific minimum targets to be met by the global community at specified dates. It has become customary for individual countries to seek to meet the global targets at the national level. These targets represent a concrete approach toward ensuring that sustainability, equity, productivity and empowerment are steadily realised. For example, by committing to halve poverty by 2015, countries need to make significant progress in productivity, equity and empowerment. By seeking to reduce child and maternal mortality, global authorities oblige themselves to maintain the postwar rates of improvement in these life indicators and achieve sustainability. The MDGs constitute eight Goals, which have been articulated into18 targets. Within these targets are 48 indicators, adopted by a consensus of experts from the United Nations Secretariat and IMF, OECD and the World Bank to measure progress towards the Goals (see Table 1). Under Goal 1, \u201cEradicate extreme poverty and hunger,\u201d for example, are two targets: (1) Halve, between 1980 and 2015, the proportion of people whose income is less than $1 a day and (2) Halve, between 1990 and 2015, the proportion of people who suffer from hunger. Some of the specific indicators for this Goal are the proportion of the population living below $1 per day, the share of the poorest quintile in national consumption, the prevalence of underweight children younger than 5 and the proportion of the population below the minimum level of dietary energy consumption. Other Goals are similarly broken out into targets and indicators (Table 1). 18 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific Three6 economic variables play a key mediating role in achieving the MDGs: (1) economic growth, (2) employment, and (3) public sector capabilities. In turn, it is important to consider the acute impact that trade policy and international trade rules have on these three mediating variables and directly on the targets, where applicable. The key argument we make in this section is that countries should align their trade policies toward achieving the MDGs. One argument is that the MDGs are a state commitment, like existing state commitments on human rights. The more persuasive argument for aligning trade policies to MDGs is that if trade outcomes persistently undermine growth, employment and public sector capabilities, insisting on achieving MDGs (because of the manner in which they are defined) will amount to implementing social policies to make up for the toll \u2013 the negative impacts \u2013 that trade policies are inflicting. With the \u201cwrong\u201d trade policies, MDG-motivated policies can turn out to be either a very costly proposition, even if funded by international donors, or a Sisyphean effort of undoing harmful human development impacts from trade. It is useful to quickly explain the channels between these mediating variables \u2013 economic growth, employment and public sector capabilities \u2013 and achievement of the MDGs. In our view, public sector \u201ccapability\u201d is the aggregate of revenue capability, expenditure capacity and efficiency, as well as the technical and managerial capacities of public sector workers. The steady and positive movements in economic growth, employment and public sector capabilities are a necessary, albeit not sufficient, 6 Income distribution could be listed as a fourth intervening economic variable. However, given the practical and political constraints impinging on publicly led redistributive policies, income distribution is the outcome of the interaction among growth, employment and public resources in most medium-term situations. For example, high economic growth with poor employment growth, or even reductions in employment absorption, will worsen the income distribution.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadat