hool and that adequate nutrition sustains mothers and their children. In poor countries, the third mediating variable, public sector capabilities in partnership with private provision (the latter being itself dependent on growth in private incomes), is important in maintaining schools to provide primary education and access to health facilities to reduce child mortality and improve maternal health. Public health, infrastructure are themselves critical to Goal 6 (combating HIV/AIDs, malaria and other diseases). Improving incomes and adequate public sector capability are needed to meet Goal 7 (ensuring environmental sustainability) since environmental distress reflects externalities that markets cannot address and therefore require social intervention and often the outcome of the poor exploiting unpriced assets to which they have physical access. This leaves Goal 3 (promoting gender equality and empowering women) and Goal 8 (developing a global partnership for development). Promoting gender equality requires public and social advocacy, intervention and regulation, which may or may not be dependent on our three mediating variables. While more resources will facilitate the achievement of gender equality, societies need to address gender concerns in more direct ways. A growing body of research exists on the gendered impact of trade liberalisation7. That export-oriented industrialisation in many developing countries has led to an increase in women\u2019s participation in the labour force is a 7 There is extensive literature on this issue; see \u00c7a atay and Ert\u00fcrk (2004) for a review. 20 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific stylised fact8. However, it is also well-established that women\u2019s employment is either concentrated in cheap manufactured goods sectors or in the informal labour force in these countries. In many export procesing zones (EPZs), where the majority of workers are women, the nature of employment is characterised by flexibility of labour contracts and longer working hours, along with low wages in unhealthy working conditions (UN 1999; Standing 1989, 1999)9. Particularly in sub-Saharan Africa, where a majority of the population earns its livelihood from agricultural production, an overwhelming majority of small farmers are women and agricultural liberalisation has had adverse impacts on their livelihoods (Fontana et al. 1998, pp.17-19). In many developing countries, men tend to engage in production of cash crops while women engage in subsistence crops, including tending the home garden. As a result, trade liberalisation, which raises incomes from cash crops, tends to widen the economic and social achievement gap between women and men (Williams 2003, p. 66). Gender-asymmetric impacts10 of trade expansion have diverse implications across countries and regions. These impacts are conditional on the interaction between gender inequalities and trade and production arrangements. While in some cases gender inequalities places limits on 8 See Berik (2000) for a contrasting case in point. Taiwanese export-oriented manufacturing after 1980 showed a decline in women\u2019s employment and coincided with an increase in gender wage inequality. This study discusses the impact on gender wage inequality of Taiwan\u2019s restructuring during this period. While higher capital intensity, induced by export orientation in Taiwan over the period, improved both men\u2019s and women\u2019s wages, Berik (2000, p. 7-9) finds that a disproportionate number of women, compared to men, lost their jobs. The shift toward salaried jobs improved men\u2019s wages while reducing the wages of women. 9 On the other hand, in the developed countries, increased trade has gone hand-in-hand with a decline observed in women\u2019s employment in the manufacturing sector (Kucera and Milberg, (2000, p.18)). 10 See \u00c7a atay (2001) for a comprehensive discussion on the relationship between trade and gender inequalities and poverty. 21 increasing in exports, in other cases they become an instrument of international competitiveness (\u00c7agatay 2001, p.33). It is important, therefore, that trade and trade policy making11 be gender-aware.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b9a689e8-711c-4b79-bf67-b9fbd36ead2b": {"__data__": {"id_": "b9a689e8-711c-4b79-bf67-b9fbd36ead2b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a4594a981eedc25727614be034462003e02128d0c5dbee12c63e91a729f31e03"}, "2": {"node_id": "ad122e3f-3768-4435-964d-c4b015b4208b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e39a4aa851c56543d7f9d562180bcf218924fe539e1a434ccdbae24c0fd74514"}}, "hash": "32449b935a62c7be7b41b776049268d6401751c07e2b77203e6f7b53464c8fcb", "text": "It is important, therefore, that trade and trade policy making11 be gender-aware. In the case of Goal 8, two specific targets directly concern the international trading regime with which developing countries must contend. Target 12 seeks 