e would have adverse impacts, particularly on poor people. High tariff rates in the United States and Canada in the textiles and clothing sector, and on agricultural products in the EU and Japan, put people who are dependent on these sectors in the developing world at a disadvantage (Stern 2003, p. 2-3). Reducing agricultural protection \u2013 including trade-distorting tariffs, quotas, other export subsidies and anti-development tariff escalation and tariff peaks \u2013 is a most important development intervention on the part of developed countries. Some estimates even emphasise how crucial these tariff reductions would be on the developing countries\u2019 side: Phasing out 11 See Keklik (2003) for a discussion on the modalities of impact assessments of international trade. 22 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific these measures would attract new investment and lead to increases in income of US$150 - $400 billion in developing countries in the five years after completing the reforms (Stern 2003, p.5). Critical steps towards this goal include the full conversion of production subsidies to income subsidies, along with the conversion of specific duties and tariff rate quotas to more transparent ad valorem tariffs. This would promote investment in export industries of developing countries. Strong efforts by industrial countries in tariff reduction in non- agricultural goods would provide access to developing countries currently subject to anti-development tariff peaks, escalation and quotas. Processed foods are particular victims of anti-development tariff escalation: Chilean fresh tomatoes come into the United States with a 2.8 percent duty; if the same tomatoes are dried and packaged, they pay 8.9 percent; however, salsa and ketchup exports into the United States pay an 11.6 percent tariff. While the tariff on cocoa beans in the EU is 0.5 percent, the tariff on chocolate is more than 30 percent. Labour-intensive manufacturers such as exporters of cotton T-shirts from China to the United States face similar escalation. To achieve the promise of the Doha Development Round, each country must take up its part of global responsibility to development. So far, the signs do not give cause for optimism. The other targets under Goal 8, which deal with the external debt problems of developing countries, are directly related to our three mediating variables \u2013 economic growth, employment and public sector capabilities \u2013 but are only tangentially related to trade, which is the focus of this paper. The results of recent research on trade policy need to be interpreted in terms of the potential impact of trade policy on MDGs. Trade liberalisation, or any other policy to increase the dependence of growth on external trade, has not been neutral across skills levels, gender and regions. Trade liberalisation usually benefits those with skills and capital, 23 which in most instances are beyond the capabilities of the poor (Vandermoortele 2003, p.11). For this reason, trade liberaliasation, in conjunction with stabilisation programmes that tend to curb the public sector\u2019s ability to boost demand and maintain social programmes, tend to leave the poor worse off. In many cases, the impact on the poor can be permanent, since trade liberalisation is intended to change permanently the kinds of sectors where different workers can participate economically. The impact is on the employment opportunities of the poorer segments of the population. Increased dependence on trade for growth also has often meant surges of imports, including those agricultural products on which many of the poor depend on their livelihood. Because of agricultural subsidies in industrial economies, these imports undercut domestic farm prices. A 2003 study states that 1.3 million Mexican farmers have lost their livelihoods after NAFTA took effect, a regional trade agreement that from Mexico\u2019s point of view constituted an accelerated process of liberalisation with two neighbouring industrial economies (Carnegie Endowment for International Peace 2003, p. 19). About 8.1 million in Mexico\u2019s active labour force worked in the agriculture sector in 1993; at the end of 2002, it was roughly 6.8 million. The report states that, though the total loss may not be attributed to NAFTA, \u201c(A)gricultural trade liberalisation linked to NAFTA is the signal most significant factor in the loss of agricultural jobs in Mexico\u201d (Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, 2003, p. 20) Precipitous", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "da8e0176-9061-49ca-8d25-3c5bf420a192": {"__data__": {"id_": "da8e0176-9061-49ca-8d25-3c5bf420a192", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6f35ff2e45f7388b8c8aa564cbe4b6c96a29fd532d6b99a6df4a64bc5d3e2694"}}, "hash": "6f35ff2e45f7388b8c8aa564cbe4b6c96a29fd532d6b99a6df4a64bc5d3e2694", "text": "import openings likewise have drastic impacts on transition economies. Table 2 presents indices of key production sectors in Mongolia for the years 1989-1998. Since 1989, real production have been reduced to almost nil in key sectors, including those for which Mongolia might have been expected to have a comparative advantage, such as woolen fabric, overcoats and suits. After liberalisation, the only sectors that have significantly increased are those related to mining and the export of bird feathers. Outputs from the mining sector and commodity 24 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific production, including bird feathers, have export markets. However, these sectors do not tend to absorb much employment in comparison to other kinds of products. These also do not lend themselves easily to broader production linkages with other sectors or to increased skill upgrading (\u201clearning by doing\u201d). It is not difficult to understand the impact on employment, the second key mediating variable, as a result of the drive for efficiency and productivity in Mongolia. Meeting MDG targets in such an economy will require a recovery of employment. At the macroeconomic level, import surges have tended to cause debt buildup and balance-of-payments crises. In most countries, such crises have hurt the poor and middle classes, who are unable to shift their assets out of the domestic currency. These crises also have led to additional fiscal stringency and cutbacks in social programmes. Trade reform and liberalisation have a direct link to public sector capability12 through reductions in trade tax revenue, which often are the largest and most reliable source of revenue in poor countries. Several theoretical studies find that tariff revenues increase with liberalisation if the initial tariff rate is higher than its revenue-maximizing level or if quantitative restrictions are replaced by tariffs so Governments capture the quota rents13; however, empirical evidence barely support these analyses. Baunsgaard and Keen (2004), using panel data covering 125 countries, find that while rich countries have been able to find other sources of revenues to make up for lost trade taxes, middle-income countries have recovered only 35 to 55 cents of revenue for every dollar lost from trade taxes, low-income countries have recovered almost none. By undercutting tax revenues, trade liberalisation creates vulnerabilities in public expenditure and capabilities that are necessary to meet Goals 2, 12 Morales (2005) reviews the different channels by which different aspects of trade reform affect fiscal policy. 13 See Winters et al. (2004, p. 104-105) for an extensive review of theoretical and empirical literature on this issue. 25 4, 5, 6 and 7. Counting only revenue losses as the sole cost of these tariff reductions would definitely underestimate actual possible losses. Revenue losses may be compensated by tax increases or by tightening Government budgets. However, the process of these compensations does not usually take into account their diverse impacts on different groups of constituents. These differential impacts usually conform to the vulnerabilities and deprivation among the marginalised and the poor14. Moreover, the hardening of intellectual property protections through trade sanctions under bilateral and regional trade agreements and under the World Trade Organization\u2019s Trade Related Intellectual Property Rights (TRIPS) regime has raised the cost of essential medicine and imposes additional pressures on public sector capability. As emphasised in the previous section, trade policy and international trade rules have a crucial impact on human development. A serious commitment in achieving MDGs demands not only serious reform of trade policies of rich countries, but it also calls for a rethinking of prevailing approaches to development strategy in poor countries, which have tended to emphasise efficiency over growth, employment and public sector capability. Without such a rethinking, MDG programmes can become a technique for treating the symptoms of low growth, unemployment or jobless growth, or deteriorating public sector capability. The alternative is to redesign trade and macroeconomic policies so that they (1) do not risk any backsliding on MDG levels already achieved and (2) increase the probability of progressively achieving MDG targets. This is a preventative approach, if not an explicitly developmental one. MDGs provide specific measurable targets and indicators that can be monitored and linked up analytically to growth, employment and public sector capability. The interaction of these three variables with trade 14 See Elson and \u00c7a atay (2000) for a discussion on social content of macroeconomic policies. 26 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific policies can, in turn, be understood in order to devise trade policies that achieve the MDGs. The experience of successful Asian countries needs to be reconsidered through an MDG lens in order to identify policy lessons from successful trade policy that can be", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e1885a46-1ab4-40ea-b75c-51b4edc60748": {"__data__": {"id_": "e1885a46-1ab4-40ea-b75c-51b4edc60748", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5a3b181dd55bca9119c103743cd07e6f1b42694e90e53b0834cc576b6d26c3a0"}, "3": {"node_id": "e68c39f1-375c-429c-9906-320d6d70b863", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "59f0221d084ead7736f3a213fc6ba97bb78f041eaad2f42c34fcbec816c87e68"}}, "hash": "c50ae30254686f5b09fdebe656bcd44441cf504a6c2c6e5f208549b7fd2075a3", "text": "incorporated in MDG-inspired policy initiatives. In the East Asian case, a strong emphasis in educational upgrading accompanied the export drive. Moreover, in the East Asian experience, the state had an increasing role15 as part of the export drive, as opposed to the current view that a declining state role is an ingredient of successful trade policy. In order to recast MDG approaches away from symptom- curing toward development-promoting, the East Asian experience needs to be better understood. If key elements of East Asian trade policies, which were MDG-consistent, are analytically distilled, it would highlight the importance of the growth-enhacing, employment- absorbing and skill-upgrading strategies in the region. 15 Aky\u00fcz (1999, p. 16) characterises the expanding role of the public sector thus: \u201cBehind the successful management of economic rents in East Asia lies a much deeper process of building a robust network of Government and business institutions consistent with strategic development goals.\u201d East Asia did not necessarily have strong public sector capabilities at the start of the drive for development. Countries such as the Republic of Korea, Japan, and Singapore sent public sector employees to the Philippines for training in modern public administration, and indirectly to upgrade their English-speaking capabilities. Philippine public sector capabilities have since lagged behind these other countries, and so has its development performance. 27 Table 1 Table 1 Table 1 Table 1 Table 1 Millenium Development Goals and Targets Millenium Development Goals and Targets Millenium Develop