vestment in production activities, distort the prices under which investment had been carried out in the past. The new approach sought a thoroughgoing restructuring of domestic industries toward those that would be internationally competitive and self-financing. This required attention to two issues: First, there was the question of the sequencing of the trade reforms and the length of period of adjustment; second, there was the question of whether investment would indeed respond to the new price structure. There are a number of studies in the literature exploring the question of what kind of liberalisation is better for economic growth. Among others, 16 See Greenaway (1993) for a review of the policy interventions. 36 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific Berg et al. (1999) analyses the evolution of output and finds that faster liberalisation is better for growth. Faster adjustment provides additional impulse to growth (Berg et.al. 1996, p. 52), confirming the results of earlier studies on countries of the former Soviet Union (De Melo et al. 1996, p. 27; Aslund 1996, p. 304-305; Sachs 1996, p. 133). In the well- known debate about shock therapy versus gradualist of adjustment process, these authors argue in favor of rapid liberalisation. The analytical justification for rapid liberalisation leaned heavily on political considerations \u2013 that gradual liberalisation, while theoretically justified, could be undermined by powerful constituencies that would be hurt by liberalisation. The political counterargument was that gradual liberalisation sustained a constituency for reform. Theorising about the gradualist approach to liberalisation basically emerged from the unfavourable outcomes of actual transition experiences in former socialist countries. Lau, Qian and Roland (2000, p. 120-124), in considering the Chinese experience, construct a theoretical model of gradual market liberalisation. They specify a dual-track pricing mechanism approach for implementing an efficient Pareto-improving transition without losers. Their proposition is consistent with institutionalist approaches to economics, drawing attention to the importance of institutions in development. The basic argument in this literature brings to the fore that institutions matter; that institutions change incrementally, and because change is path-dependent, Governments that do not have full information about the path would be better off implementing reforms gradually17. Other studies consider the issue of the impact of external liberalisation on poverty reduction. Dollar (2001) argues that the only developing 17 Sachs, Woo and Yang (2000, p.13) provide a counter argument that states that information on the most efficient institutions are already out there via evolution in advanced countries, so latecomers should mimic these in an optimal period to reduce losses within a particular political environment.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "25fede28-15d7-4957-ad29-5b89411ff6b9": {"__data__": {"id_": "25fede28-15d7-4957-ad29-5b89411ff6b9", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ec90cd776fc81952ae0f76cc7f1585124c3ff5ce7c73e3514de9b2a8f47df416"}, "2": {"node_id": "3f207150-b488-4d1d-923c-8f94f2f85e1a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "73a557eaa52185861934ca11e4ee4c7d4a5c983fee935a0fdb4bb33e252a592d"}}, "hash": "c9b6d8a92bb171a83107047c4a942cf3577e53f3e2f2547943d6a4ab020fea20", "text": "37 countries that show faster growth and significant reduction in poverty \u2013 i.e., income poverty \u2013 are those that also have performed faster trade and investment liberalisation. As expected, Dollar finds that faster growth comes with significant poverty reduction. Integration has been a positive force for the well-being of people in the developing world (Dollar 2001, p. 35). This buttresses one of the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3ad53312-e573-4d84-98aa-c451584ae0b3": {"__data__": {"id_": "3ad53312-e573-4d84-98aa-c451584ae0b3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bdee18aa136a7ab20df6a5f9d941b7f01a6358a637ba06147ed79ba3aac1c441"}, "3": {"node_id": "79681032-9c05-489c-ba51-115b4b268e7a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4e99bb132b78f28305ed700497e78b632dec9f6260aa0f684420be8dcc3366ba"}}, "hash": "edd940a12bc676dd6a15a534a48ee5c3bcb9d4f354a0cf540d34ae0a9cdf3514", "text": "propositions of neoclassical growth theory arguing that, ceteris paribus, poor countries grow faster than their counterparts, strengthening the underpinnings of the view \u201cgrowth is good for the poor.\u201d Other studies ask the question \u201cHow good is growth?\u201d Wade (2004) asserts that world income distribution has become more unequal over the past several decades. This unequalising impact intensified in 1980s and 1990s (Wade 2001, p. 8). Milanovic (2004) also finds adverse impacts of openness on the poor, by evaluating the impact on relative income shares of high and low deciles. This study argues that openness is only good for middle- and high-income countries, where the relative income of the poor and the middle class rises compared to the rich (Milanovic 2004, p. 13). The expected next question is: Does an unequal distribution of income have an impact on economic growth? Inequality generates the risk of contraining the growth of even the rich countries. A 2001 ILO paper suggests both theoretically and empirically that income distribution matters for growth associated with poverty reduction and that income distribution in turn matters for growth. The authors argue that when \u2018Growth is neutral to income distribution,\u2019 growth per se is not sufficient to reduce income inequality. They also find that: 1) greater distributional equality provides a favourable \u201cinitial condition\u201d for rapid and sustainable growth; 2) redistribution of current income and assets, or redistribution of an economy\u2019s growth increment, is the most effective form of poverty reduction for most countries; and 3) the mechanisms to achieve the redistributions are feasible for most countries. (Dagdeviren et al. 2001, p. 23). The study lists a policy agenda based on the model that 38 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific includes progressive taxation, transfer payments, human resource development and country-specific infrastructure and public works policies (Dagdeviren et al. 2001, pp. 19-22). Given these unsettled debates, it would be helpful to look at the East Asian countries\u2019 experiences termed as \u201cEast Asian miracle\u201d in more depth. Lessons from a \u201csuccessful\u201d integration to the world economy also may give some idea on how to exploit potential interlinkages between trade liberalisation, growth and investment, in order to achieve economic development alongside human development goals. East Asia\u2019s Strategic Integration East Asia\u2019s Strategic Integration East Asia\u2019s Strategic Integration East Asia\u2019s Strategic Integration East Asia\u2019s Strategic Integration In East Asia, success in export-oriented industrialisation drew an increasing proportion of the labour force into manufacturing and depended on steadily improving agricultural productivity. Increased light manufacturing exports permitted a steady improvement in the conditions of work, especially in rural areas. As globalisation expanded in the 1980s, many Asian countries succeeded in drawing in assembly and low-skill export-oriented production to absorb domestic labour. Since the 1990s, this approach to international economic integration has become the norm. This approach can be contrasted with the earlier East Asia approach, which sought a strategic integration and steady improvements in livelihood and productivity for workers. Because this alternative strategy relies heavily on the attraction of low labour costs, increased competition among countries for foreign investment has seen the weakening of labour protections, especially in export processing zones, where enterprises tend to rely heavily on female labour. Trade liberalisation though enhanced women\u2019s employment opportunities coincided with wage discrimination against women, even in East Asia (Taiwan, Republic of Korea) because of increasing competition from international trade (Berik et al. 2004, p. 17). Beyond this fact, evidence also exists on liberalisation providing strong incentives to keep women\u2019s wages comparatively lower in order to attract foreign 39 direct investment and be competitive in international markets. Braunstein and Epstein (2002), looking at China\u2019s export processing zones, demonstrate this fact. These findings suggest the importance of a gendered analysis of wage inequality and underline the fact that the gender impacts of trade liberalisation provide a different and rarely told dimension of the East Asian miracle. It is also important to point out a key analytical difference between the East Asian strategy and the standard economic theory (often referred to as the Hecksher Ohlin Samuelson model), which has laid the basis for the strategy of low labou costs as the strategy for international economic integration. The standard model takes the level of employment as exogenous, normally at full employment.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "79681032-9c05-489c-ba51-115b4b268e7a": {"__data__": {"id_": "79681032-9c05-489c-ba51-115b4b268e7a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bdee18aa136a7ab20df6a5f9d941b7f01a6358a637ba06147ed79ba3aac1c441"}, "2": {"node_id": "3ad53312-e573-4d84-98aa-c451584ae0b3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "edd940a12bc676dd6a15a534a48ee5c3bcb9d4f354a0cf540d34ae0a9cdf3514"}}, "hash": "4e99bb132b78f28305ed700497e78b632dec9f6260aa0f684420be8dcc3366ba", "text": "The standard model takes the level of employment as exogenous, normally at full employment. The main driving forces in the standard model are relative differences in labour costs and differences between production sectors in their need for labour input. The key conclusion of the standard model is that trade between economies (of the type specified by the model) will raise wages and productivity in the trading countries. As intended, the gain is solely in efficiency after goods production and labour", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9754aa98-9715-4eba-81f3-15ee3df71b9d": {"__data__": {"id_": "9754aa98-9715-4eba-81f3-15ee3df71b9d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b7b9c1b1d08c2495f0ef27d0d92a2a5ed7d47f16798c01fc654c3170c5788a61"}, "3": {"node_id": "52a3a97d-034a-4b19-a74e-39eebca2d490", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7e7b18cc001573ff52e043227520af8356daace39064cb4c9df80b306f670a62"}}, "hash": "82b8c770b3811d8a6ee1f54242424d6cc207f2f840a7ac123d36b89993bca1d6", "text": "are reallocated across sectors. The model has nothing to say about changes in total employment, which is an exogenous variable. The East Asian approach wrestled with the issue of raising total employment and productivity simultaneously. East Asian countries sought to eliminate poverty instead of positioning the economy for growth by sustaining it18. For this purpose, the strategy deployed industries that would temporarily be inefficient by world standards as long as it absorbed labour, especially from agriculture, where labour 18 For an alternative view, see Seguino (2000). Her empirical analysis, based on a data set of middle-income semi-industrialised economies with varying degrees of export orientation, indicates that across countries, and over time within countries, there is a positive link between gender wage inequality and growth. Gender-wage inequality works as a stimulating factor for investment (Seguino 2000, p.1221-23). 40 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific working with fixed resources had low productivity. In surveying the application of the standard model during the age of trade liberalisation, Hoekman and Winters (2005) find that as predicted by the standard model, there are indeed no significant increases in total employment in liberalising countries, even as there is scattered evidence of efficiency gains. Trade is also associated with increased wage and income inequality within countries through two channels: (1) increased pressure for technological upgrading to attain international competitiveness, which tends to bid up the wages of skilled labour and (2) the (implicit) expansion of the unskilled pool of labour as more poor countries contribute their labour supply in worldwide production activities (Wood 1995, 1997). It is possible that the impact of trade liberalisation on wage inequality is peculiar to poorer countries, i.e., countries that have incomes below the world median income. Milanovic and Squire (2005) find that tariff reduction leads to higher inter-occupational (i.e., skill or education) premiums and inter-industry inequality in poorer countries. The Interaction of Investment and Trade Liberalisation The Interaction of Investment and Trade Liberalisation The Interaction of Investment and Trade Liberalisation The Interaction of Investment and Trade Liberalisation The Interaction of Investment and Trade Liberalisation It is estimated that two-thirds of achieved liberalisation was undertaken by countries on a unilateral basis, as opposed to a reciprocal manner with other countries. Tables 3 and 4 summarise trends in tariff averages for developing countries since the 1980s, for both unweighted and weighted averages respectively. Trade liberalisation involved not only tariff reductions, but also involved the dismantling of quantitative restrictions and the dismantling of state trading companies. Tariff changes therefore are an incomplete accounting of the extent of trade opening. Nevertheless, both tables indicate a clear and strong trend toward more liberalised trade worldwide since 1980. South, East, and Southeast Asia had the highest (weighted) average tariffs at the start of period and in the most recent period have an average tariff lower than other regions. In 2000, North Africa and Central America and the Caribbean exhibited the 41 highest average tariffs. Tables 3 and 4 suggest that Asian countries have liberalised as much as the rest of the world. Tables 5 and 6 present the trends of foreign trade share in GDP, as export and import shares respectively. While export shares in all regions in the world increased in the 1990s compared to the 1960s and 1970s, South, East and Southeast Asia display the highest change (Table 5). Table 5 also shows how crucial has been in the 1990s for countries in South, East and Southeast Asia, excluding China. Export share in GDP is as high as 43 percent in that decade (Table 5). The same tendency also is observed in import shares (Table 6). Again, South, East and Southeast Asia register the highest increases in the last three decades and, excluding China, trade volume comprised almost 85 percent of GDP in the region. While the volume of trade, i.e., the sum of exports and imports , as a share of GDP increased by 20 percent in the world (from 35 percent to 42 percent) in South, East and Southeast Asia, trade volume expanded its share to more than six times higher than world trade (31 percent to 73 percent) (Tables 5 and 6). Following extensive liberalisation policies, trade has become the dominant proportion of income worldwide. Nevertheless, this is still more significant for the South, East and Southeast Asian region.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "52a3a97d-034a-4b19-a74e-39eebca2d490": {"__data__": {"id_": "52a3a97d-034a-4b19-a74e-39eebca2d490", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https:/