a-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5c727f3093c0a8ff0e1861871d8d2140b25c661ee1400c15a758eade5acb54cd"}, "3": {"node_id": "2bc13aed-8640-4946-a63c-b5f62039ac35", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5732ac72e1c79af1434607223c67938d7d489d8551f1af55c66d0efd37112185"}}, "hash": "ceb26635f3b7fd36586280fa85cdd1f91797410eb6b8c5544b48b02c4c4d9512", "text": "variable, then the annual average growth rate in percentage is obtained by: (exp(b)-1)*100%. 2:2:2:2:2: 1950s corresponds to the years from 1950 to 1959. 1960 is included in the 1960s. The same rule applies to 1960s, \u201970s, \u201980s and \u201990s unless otherwise noted. 3:3:3:3:3: 1990s corresponds to the years from 1992 to 1999 for Central Asia figures. 48 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific While Asian developing countries have liberalised their trade regimes since the 1980s to the same measure as countries in other regions, contrasts exists with regard to economic performance during the period. The era of trade liberalisation coincided with lower economic growth rates in most regions and most countries (see Tables 7 and 8). For many countries, 1980 represents a watershed year. World per-capita GDP growth declined from 2.2 percent in the 1970s to 1.7 percent in the 1980s \u2013 and to zero in the 1990s (Table 7). These trends are confirmed in real GDP growth rates in Table 8. One element in the world average is the drastic fall in economic growth rates in Central and Eastern Europe during the chaotic transition away from central planning in the 1990s; however, in the 1980s these countries still experienced growth. Since the 1980s, Africa follows the worldwide decline in growth in overall GDP and in per-capita GDP. Latin America (grouped under \u201cAmerica\u201d in Tables 7 and 8, consisting of Central America, the Caribbean and South America), experienced a drastic decline in growth in the 1980s, the region\u2019s lost decade of the debt crisis; it has not recovered the growth rates of earlier periods. Per-capita growth rates in Asia contradict the overall trend and explain the recovery of per-capita growth rates for developing countries as a whole. The last row of Table 7 indicates that, without China\u2019s growth rates, Asia\u2019s growth rates also would exhibit a decline, albeit a more modest one. For Africa and Latin America in particular, the period of trade liberalisation has been associated with markedly reduced growth rates. Trade reforms in these regions were undertaken within broader reform efforts, which included privatisation and deregulation. Moreover, many countries in these two regions experienced balance-of-payments crises, debt restructuring and fiscal policy compression. During the same period, most Asian economies also were undergoing the same thoroughgoing policy reform processes, but for the most part, avoided the macroeconomic crises that accompanied these policy shifts in the other 49 regions. The one exception was the Asian financial crises, induced by capital account liberalisation, which swept through Southeast Asia and the Republic of Korea in 1997-98, from which the affected countries have now recovered. In searching for a proximate explanation for the different experience during the period of trade liberalisation/expansion, changes in the rate of investment suggest themselves. The 1980s package of reforms were oriented to expanding the role of the private sector in the economy, responding to improved price signals as a result of the dismantling of distortionary state policies. Investment rates not only have a direct and short-term impact on growth, but these also should reflect the efficacy of relying more heavily on the private sector in developmental terms.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2bc13aed-8640-4946-a63c-b5f62039ac35": {"__data__": {"id_": "2bc13aed-8640-4946-a63c-b5f62039ac35", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5c727f3093c0a8ff0e1861871d8d2140b25c661ee1400c15a758eade5acb54cd"}, "2": {"node_id": "d728eb19-7f22-4a36-b229-466a490763ad", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ceb26635f3b7fd36586280fa85cdd1f91797410eb6b8c5544b48b02c4c4d9512"}}, "hash": "5732ac72e1c79af1434607223c67938d7d489d8551f1af55c66d0efd37112185", "text": "50 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific Table 9 Table 9 Table 9 Table 9 Table 9 Annual Average Investment Share of GDP (%) Annual Average Investment Share of GDP (%) Annual Average Investment Share of GDP (%) Annual Average Investment Share of GDP (%) Annual Average Investment Share of GDP (%) Regions Regions Regions Regions Regions 1950s 195