 only region, except for the grouping of developed countries, in which there is an increase in the investment ratio. It is critical to work out the nexus between the buildup in the external sector and investment in the Asian context. Aky\u00fcz (1999) emphasises the key role that domestic savings out of profits play. Exports and domestic investment provide the income growth that generates the profits. These profits can then be reinvested in response to the demand stimulus from exports and domestic investment themselves. However, there is no guarantee that higher profits from trade expansion would stimulate significantly higher domestic investment; this is how Rodrik (1999) interprets the case of Chile and Turkey in the 1980s. The state certainly has a role in securing property rights and preventing the buildup of macroeconomic imbalances that lead to economic crises. In the East Asian case, however, the state had a critical role in encouraging the mobilisation of super-normal profits (rents) and providing incentives to direct these to reinvestment (as opposed to consumption) and export production expansion. As Weiss (2005, p. 14) explains: Of the countries concerned, aspects of industrial policy were found in all cases except Hong Kong, China, with the most extensive set of interventions in Republic of Korea and Taipei, China; the least in Singapore, with Thailand, Indonesia and Malaysia falling somewhere in between. The result in all cases was that profitability in manufacturing 52 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific was raised relative to services and in most cases also relative to agriculture. This is far from unusual, since it is the standard outcome under import substitution regimes. The state\u2019s role went beyond securing property rights; it involved providing a secure environment for private investment into manufacturing and export expansion. The state becomes a key player in the operation of an \u201caccumulation regime\u201d (Liepitz 1998, p. 23), which can coordinate the restructuring of production through investment. While the classic Asian tigers were paragons of accumulation, the examples are not only historical. The current structural transformations occurring in China in the context of high growth partake of the same type of process and, by some interpretations, amount to no less than capitalist development (McNally 2004). In East Asia, \u201cgetting prices right\u201d has not been as important as expanding markets and growing investment. Public investment as a share of GDP for selected countries confirms positively these propositions. While in the 1980s public investment as a share of GDP shows huge declines in Argentina, Chile and Turkey; figures indicate increases in the Republic of Korea, Malaysia and Thailand (Table 10). Among others, Argentina\u2019s public investment ratio recorded the highest fall (46 percent) in the 1980s compared to the 1970s (from 9.11 percent to 4.90 percent).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a56e8b94-b018-4710-91da-6fa1727f52a6": {"__data__": {"id_": "a56e8b94-b018-4710-91da-6fa1727f52a6", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ea73824b3dfb9ce75f70d