en in Figure 1, while in the late 1970s the annual average share of capital goods exports in total exports was lower than 5 percent in Thailand, around 10 percent in Malaysia and almost 20 percent in the Republic of Korea, by 2000 the figures increased dramatically, to higher than 30, 50 and 45 percent respectively. Similarly, in China, on average, around 8 percent of total exports were capital goods in the 1980s, which increased to more than 20 percent in 1990s. Furthermore, in the first half of the current decade the shares in all countries register much higher figures: more than 40 percent in Thailand, almost 60 percent in Malaysia, more than 60 percent in the Republic of Korea, and almost 40 percent in China. Thus, we can safely argue, as Figure 1 confirms, that countries in East 54 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific Asia successfully shifted their exports to high-value added capital goods \u2013 i.e., intermediate goods \u2013 particularly in the 1990s, following strategic trade and industrial policies applied in the 1960s and 1970s. On the other hand, when we compare the figures in selected East Asian countries with Argentina, Chile or Turkey, we notice that more than 90 percent of total exports are non-capital goods in the 1980s. Capital goods shares show a rise in theh 1990s, but go beyond 10 percent only slightly in Argentina and Turkey, whereas they barely reach 6 percent of total exports in Chile. From 2000 to 2004, among the three only Turkey registers a higher figure (24 percent). We observe almost no change in this millennium compared to the 1990s in the cases of Chile and Argentina. Figure 1: Data Source: Data Source: Data Source: Data Source: Data Source: The United Nation Statistical Division (UNSD) Commodity Trade (COMTRADE) Database that contains Exports and Imports by Commodity and Partner Country. Note: Note: Note: Note: Note: Shares of capital goods in total exports are calculated using SITC Rev.2 classification. Capita