ype": "Report"}, "hash": "d8a376ec70c24ce9315600a073d4a73adeb37a1833501c7c6a6a1970b3945b73"}}, "hash": "d8a376ec70c24ce9315600a073d4a73adeb37a1833501c7c6a6a1970b3945b73", "text": "figures for high- technology exports shares within manufacturing. For instance, in Malaysia almost 40 percent of manufacturing exports by the end of the 1980s were high-technology products. Thailand and the Republic of Korea follow, at 18 and 17 percent respectively, whereas in Turkey the share was only 1.6 percent over the same years. One reason is that in Turkey an export-oriented regime was launched only in 1980. In the 1990s, the Republic of Korea and Thailand showed around a 30 percent increase compared to the 1980s and rose to 24 and 25 percent respectively. Over the same period, more than 45 percent of manufacturing exports were high-technology exports in Malaysia. Again, Turkey registers a very low figure, around 2 percent. Chile and Argentina followed Turkey at 3 and 6 percent. Compared to East Asian countries, these figures are too low. Almost all manufacturing exports were low-technology, labour-intensive goods, although these countries also fully liberalised their trade regimes at the beginning of the last decade. In considering the years between 2000 and 2003, China\u2019s high- technology exports share exhibits a big jump and more than doubles, to 22 percent from around 10 percent. The largest change after China was observed in the Turkish economy, which increased to almost 4 percent, yet still low in comparison to Malaysia (58 percent), Thailand (32 percent) and the Republic of Korea (32 percent). In Argentina and Chile, the corresponding figures are 9 and 4 percent respectively. Thus, Figures 1 and 2 demonstrate clearly the East Asian economies\u2019 strategy aimed at expanding exports, but these countries also achieved higher productivity via technological upgrading in their export sectors. The composition of export goods has changed drastically in Malaysia, the Republic of Korea, Thailand since the end of 1980s and, more recently, in China. In contrast to East Asian countries, other developing economies that also completed 57 liberalisation in the mid-1980s were locked into low-technology export products. A key distinguishing characteristic of East Asian economies has been the states\u2019 active trade and industrial strategy. Yet export-oriented regimes were launched with state interventions in other developing countries as well. Thus, a broader examination is required to evaluate the structural differences. The East Asian strategy cannot be seen as a major success in isolation to the characteristics of the international economic environment in which it occurred. Moreover, it would be ahistorical to derive easy lessons from East Asian experience. Nevertheless, we believe comparisons reveal at least what a strategic industrial policy is and what it is not. Also, emphasising crucial factors in success stories might be the first step for new successes. On the other hand, the East Asian strategy might be an appropriate reference point to assess the relative failures of other strategies, or those cases of no strategy. There is room for developing countries to replicate the strategy in a different form, depending on specific structural characteristics of their economies and international opportunities, if they are willing to seriously consider a more active role for the state. The success of the East Asian strategy relied upon rapid industrialisation and higher export potential and, hence, higher rates of economic growth. This brings us to a critical point: Is a strategic industrial policy enough for growth? This type of economic transformation does not guarantee that human development outcomes will be attained. What about the quality of growth? The East Asian economies, and recently China, had the starting advantage of high literacy and educational attainment at the start of growth. The Republic of Korea, meanwhile, is well known for its enormous investment in education during its growth process. Public spending per primary school-age student in Korea increased more than tenfold 58 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific between 1970 and 1995 (Thomas et.al. 2000, p. 69-70). In 1995, 17 percent of GDP per capita was allocated to primary education spending. Considering the large number of students in primary schools, it would not be an overstatement to argue that even this figure underestimates the amount of public expenditure in education, particularly in primary education (tertiary education was mainly supported by private investment). More than 60 percent of total spending to education was allocated to primary education (Thomas et.al. 2000, p. 68). The report also notes that in the Republic Korea, households assume a 30 to 50 percent share of total expenditure for educational costs (Thomas et.al. 2000, p. 68-69). In this regard, as in the nexus between trade and investment, the role of the state has been indispensable in sustaining social expenditures. 59 V. Livelihood and Employment Safe, dignified, meaningful participation in society\u2019s production activities is an individual", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bc483023-a4b4-463b-8aa0-4f193d642998": {"__data__": {"id_": "bc483023-a4b4-463b-8aa0-4f193d642998", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e001e21f7a1682842736220d7bbbd5b65c2f368643e87c69af77a80fe5517b7c"}}, "hash": "e001e21f7a1682842736220d7bbbd5b65c2f368643e87c69af77a80fe5517b7c", "text": "right enshrined in Articles 23 and 24 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. \u201cLivelihood\u201d is a preferred concept because not all participation in production partakes of remuneration in exchange for work. In almost all societies, this is especially the case of women\u2019s participation in society\u2019s production. Women\u2019s work to provide food and sanitation, health services is critical in sustaining labour\u2019s productivity. Changes in trade rules affect access to these services. In farm communities, women not only participate in planting and harvesting activities but often have primary responsibility to supply critical inputs needed to control pests and maintain the topsoil. End of Quota-Managed Trade in Textile and Clothing End of Quota-Managed Trade in Textile and Clothing End of Quota-Managed Trade in Textile and Clothing End of Quota-Managed Trade in Textile and Clothing End of Quota-Managed Trade in Textile and Clothing19 19 19 19 19 The management of the international trade in textiles and clothing through quotas provided opportunities for many countries in the Asia- Pacific, saddled with limited industrial capacity, to mobilise their unskilled labour force for export production. In many countries, the textile quota system confirmed and rigidified a production system in which, except for the contribution of low-cost labour, all other inputs were imported and very little attention was paid to increasing the domestic value contribution to exported goods or breaking out of the ruinous competition for international buyers seeking low-cost production. The elimination of the quota system at the end of 2004 is a watershed event for Asia\u2019s developing countries. Countries that had domestic capability to compete internationally or had built such a capacity during the quota period were expected to maintain or even increase their international participation in the sector. Countries whose only advantage had been in the provision of low-cost labour would lose their textile and 19 This section draws heavily from UNDP Asia Trade Initiative (2005). 60 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific garment industries. Most especially disadvantaged are the Least Developed Countries, such as Bangladesh, Lao PDR and Nepal; these countries are doubly disadvantaged by the fact that their domestic markets are too small to support further investment in the industry. Other countries, such as the Philippines, which never developed an integrated capacity to produce textiles and garments, had been losing international market share even before the quota elimination (Jocson- Agoncillo 2004); the end of quotas is expected to only hasten the demise of these sectors. The losers are countries that relied only on their low labour costs to integrate internationally. Within these countries, female workers are particularly disadvantaged since they had been winners under the strategy of low labour costs. The gainers are countries that used the period of low-cost exports to invest domestically in integrating production, upgrading capital inputs and labour productivity. The removal of quotas should lead to an overall increase in exports of textiles and clothing from Asian countries. The global market for imports of textiles and clothing could reach US$ 600 billion by 2015, even assuming a modest growth rate of 5.3 percent per year for the next 12 years in the clothing sector and an even smaller growth rate of 3.2 percent in textiles. Conditional on sustained competitiveness, most Asian countries, taken in aggregate, stand to claim a growing portion of this ever-increasing sector. However, it is feared that the elimination of the remaining quotas may lead to major shifts in trade and investment flows across regions, provoking a global wave of consolidated, large-scale production in fewer places, with wholesale buyers shrinking the number of countries as sources of imports and outsourcing arrangements. For example, the U.S. Department of Commerce estimates the countries of major sourcing to drop to 50 percent of current levels in 2005 and to 25 per cent by 2010. Moreover, expectations of benefits and losses within Asia are unevenly 61 spread, the smaller countries with poorer infrastructure and higher input costs likely losing out to bigger players. To some extent, this fear is exaggerated, as the expanding global textile and clothing market could provide opportunities for all suppliers, including those selling at different price levels and those specialising in market niches. Countries like China and India are seen as the biggest gainers in the post-quota scenario if one looks at their current share of clothing exports to non-quota markets. For China, that share was 79 percent in 2001, suggesting that the quota system had severely restricted its exports. At the same time, the majority of its existing production emanates from state-related enterprises, which will increasingly need to face tougher reform conditions. For the East Asian tigers in an earlier", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "969590f6-881e-4efb-81bd-4f81221d3d08": {"__data__": {"id_": "969590f6-881e-4efb-81bd-4f81221d3d08", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fc731d960c31f03dc464349461f20d21f0dca339cf115b4dc08ed2381ba259d2"}}, "hash": "fc731d960c31f03dc464349461f20d21f0dca339cf115b4dc08ed2381ba259d2", "text": "period, the exploitation of trade as a source of employment creation and productivity employment relied heavily on a conscious domestic effort not to accept \u2013 even to transcend \u2013 the given international terms of trade. In responding to the difficulties generated by the elimination of textile quotas, clever adaptations of this kind of approach are necessary. Countries need to design strategies to consolidate their market access beyond their ability to contribute low- cost labour. Cambodia, for example, consolidated its access to external garment markets by setting up a system by which the Government certifies exporters based on standards designed in cooperation with the International Labor Organization. These certifications affirm that these exports were produced in factories that conform to international labour standards. With the expiration of quotas, key international buyers have actually increased their purchases from Cambodia, because it helps them avoid the \u201csweatshop\u201d label in advanced-country markets. Instead of selling Cambodia as a source of cheap labour, Cambodia has sold itself as a reliable, reasonable-cost supplier because it enhances labour rights. Countries should explore other strategies to remake themselves into the inescapable supplier. Branding, getting into the design and fashion aspects of the industry, and enhancing domestic value-added through industrial upgrading where feasible, need to be addressed now. In facing 62 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific this problem, countries should take the view that the world market begins at home, that winning the world market requires winning the domestic market first, with quality goods at a reasonable price (a standard that also applies in world markets). And winning world markets only through cheap labour that cannot afford to consume what it produces is a strategy that is increasingly non-viable, at least in the textile and clothing sector. In taking seriously their home markets, Asian countries need to develop productive, income-earning livelihoods for all their workers. For certain countries, this will also require a withdrawal (if possible, orderly) from the textile and clothing sector altogether, so that their citizens can move to more stable, income-earning work in other industries. This kind of adjustment will require conscious efforts and resources among the Government, the private sector and labour. A domestic strategy is a sine qua non to an international diplomatic strategy. A key element of such an international strategy is the granting of preferential access to garment and textile exports from LDCs, a group of countries that already recognized by industrial economies as deserving of special treatment. Preferential access can alleviate the dislocation of employment and provide the resources for adjustment required by these countries that would otherwise have to be raised from meagre LDC incomes. Asian countries can pursue three general kinds of strategies: (1) measures to deepen international market access, (2) measures to foster domestic competitiveness and export performance, and (3) measures to mitigate the impact of quota elimination on human development. Under measures to deepen international market access, Asian LDCs in particular need to seize the moral ground and to obligate developed countries to provide duty- and quota-free access for all their exports. This request is part of a broader Doha Ministerial mandate that required that Special and Differential Treatment (SDT) become \u201cmore precise, effective and operational.\u201d There has been little movement in this regard, 63 however. LDCs need to succeed in enshrining special and differential treatment as a governing principle of the WTO, not merely as exceptions to the general rules, so that they can accept obligations that are commensurate with their stage of development. SDT should become legally binding through the dispute settlement mechanism of the WTO. Other appropriate measures include requiring tighter disciplines (narrower grounds) on the use of anti-dumping and countervailing duties; incorporating the textile and clothing sector in all Generalized System of Preference schemes; removing quota restraints on countries currently in the process of joining the WTO; and engaging in mutually beneficial regional integration efforts. To foster domestic competitiveness and export performance, countries can intensify their efforts to facilitate trade; ease the processes of importing intermediate inputs to export products; adopt measures to reduce input costs on power, transport and key raw materials; promote in-country knowledge and capabilities about markets; create investment funds and consolidate credit support for small- and medium-scale industries; enhance labour productivity; invest in nurturing reputation, brands and images; and obtain technical and financial assistance for trade facilitation from developed countries in accordance with their commitment on Goal 8 of the Millennium Development Goals. Among the possible measures to mitigate the adverse impact on human development, countries should consider implementing a comprehensive labour restructuring program (including widespread retraining); adopt and enforce legislation on decent work;", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4ddd5de5-9e99-4105-be0c-88d24cc7a72a": {"__data__": {"id_": "4ddd5de5-9e99-4105-be0c-88d24cc7a72a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9e65608f3638717293858087634e2834f514052f6ac27514bd0884955dd6a5a7"}}, "hash": "9e65608f3638717293858087634e2834f514052f6ac27514bd0884955dd6a5a7", "text": "implement guidelines for responsible practices on the closure of plants; conduct human development impact assessments of trade policies to explore employment options; identify and explore opportunities for export diversification within the textile and clothing sector and beyond; and guard against worsening balance-of-payments problems as a result of falling textile and clothing exports. 64 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific Temporary International Movement of Labour Temporary International Movement of Labour Temporary International Movement of Labour Temporary International Movement of Labour Temporary International Movement of Labour A large number of developing countries would be greatly benefited by improved access to service markets by their workers. If entry quotas were increased by 3 percent of OECD countries\u2019 labour force, the global welfare gains will be US $158 to $200 billion per year20. In assessing the potential contribution of the Movement of Natural Persons (MNP) to human development, one can examine the improved employment opportunities, and the value of remittances for communities and families as a means of poverty alleviation and as a source of investment funds for SMEs. Total remittances for developing countries from their nationals working abroad exceeded US$50 billion in 2001. For many Asian countries, the remittances of the temporary migrants represent an important part of the GDP: Sri Lanka (6 percent), Bangladesh (4 percent), as well as an increasing percentage of total exports (in 1999, remittances amounted to 21 percent of exports in India, and 29 percent in Bangladesh). For the men and women of the developing countries, temporary migration is an opportunity to dramatically increase their earnings (more when less skilled). By diversifying sources of income, remittances reduce the vulnerability of the poor communities to domestic economic crises. It increases the wages of those remaining at home, especially when there is a surplus labour force or when the wage sector itself is in decline. In procyclical sectors, such as construction, it would allow the movement of workers to growing markets when the home country is in crisis. Remittances also can feed the extended family safety nets, thus securing the sustainability of their human development and enhancing their access to health and education when those are relatively costly. Moreover, remittances can be used to finance small local businesses, which can have a big impact in local communities. Temporary migration also provides people with the opportunity to 20 IOM-OECD (2003). 65 upgrade their skills, providing their home country with new knowledgte after their return. MNP improves returning migrants\u2019 future employment opportunities and also contributes to the overall competitiveness of the country and its ability to attract investment. These new capabilities are not only limited to economic activities; they also can have a political content, since sojourns abroad expose migrants to new ideas and social arrangements, thus promoting community empowerment. A recent World Bank report examining Philippine households\u2019 responses finds that increases in remittances enhances \u201chuman capital\u201d accumulation and entrepreneurship in \u201corigin\u201d households (households from whence the foreign worker originates) and examines Philippine households' responses to overseas members' economic shocks21. In some sectors, the temporary migration is predominantly female, facilitating the empowerment of women members of their communities. MNP is often essential for increasing the capability of developing-country enterprises to participate in international trade in many dynamic service sectors. This is particularly true of labour-intensive sectors like tourism, professional and business services, audio-visual services, construction and sectors requiring unskilled workers, as well as for high-technology sectors such as software and energy services. Temporary migration also can have undesirable social effects that should be addressed at both the international and national levels. From a human development perspective, the negative effects of MNP can include brain drain, increasing social inequality, the social consequences of the separation of family members, and the exploitation and abuse of workers; these require corrective action through national policies or bilateral agreements. Potential negative effects would differ between countries 21 The results of the study suggests that positive income shocks to migrants\u2019 earnings, such as changes in exchange rates, lead to greater child schooling, reduced child labour and increased educational expenditure in origin households. More favourable exchange rate shocks also raise hours worked in self-employment and lead to greater entry into relatively capital-intensive enterprises by migrants\u2019 origin households (Yang 2005, p.29). 66 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific depending on a variety of factors, including educational levels and cultural differences. Affected countries should integrate MNP into their overall development strategy and diplomatic interventions, and develop supportive measures to ensure the adequate training of persons working abroad and protect the vulnerable against exploitation and abuse while abroad. They should provide incentives and deterrents to prevent", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dc81e2ed-1472-4235-b8c3-88724723f5f1": {"__data__": {"id_": "dc81e2ed-1472-4235-b8c3-88724723f5f1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8333f917655cd6330e54fcc4b4b9546186f0d7442d9fdd892a8c70f3d6a0f580"}}, "hash": "8333f917655cd6330e54fcc4b4b9546186f0d7442d9fdd892a8c70f3d6a0f580", "text": "permanent migration and facilitate the effective investment of income generated through MNP at home. Brain drain would normally result from permanent migration and not MNP, as defined in GATS. However, individuals tend to migrate permanently in order to maintain the income gains achieved initially through MNP and to reduce the uncertainty created by stringent access systems that do not discriminate in favour of MNP versus permanent migration, thus promoting brain drain. In this sense, the interested parties should promote the establishment of a GATS visa, in order to ensure and facilitate temporary access to markets. There is also an important category of labour migration that partakes of forced labour, the most publicly discussed category of which is trafficking for sex work. The ILO estimates the number of global victims of forced labour to be 12.3 million (ILO 2005). Compared to the world population, this estimate implies that there are 2 victims of forced labour per 1,000 people. Compared to the global work force, the estimate corresponds to 4 persons per 1,000 workers. ILO (2005) interprets these comparisons to mean that with the proper legislation and enforcement, a solution to the global problem is quite reachable. It estimates that 20 percent of all forced labour is controlled directly by the state or armed forces, and the other 80 percent by private agents. Forced commercial sexual exploitation accounts for 11 percent of all cases and 64 percent for economic exploitation. Five percent is the estimate for work that cannot be classified in any of these areas. International cooperation to provide labour protections in receiving countries and to install a global regime that would substantially eliminate forced labour is required. 67 The current structure of MNP commitments under GATS does not provide meaningful access to foreign labour markets and discriminates against the poor, exacerbating inequalities. The extent of commitments under Mode 4 has been quite limited and largely of a generic nature. Moreover, these commitments have only bound existing access for executive and technical personnel of trans-national corporations. They do not cover the various categories of professionals and workers where developing countries have a comparative advantage because of cost, educational or cultural factors, making their specialised workers attractive in world markets. Moreover, the majority of countries have maintained the right to use limitations in market access and Most Favoured Nation status in their GATS schedules of specific commitments under Mode 4. The use of Economic Needs Tests and licensing requirements is widespread, and temporary migrants suffer because of the lack of recognition of their professional qualifications. Guidelines related to the criteria, duration and procedures of application of these limitations, and the recognition of qualifications, should be developed multilaterally. GATS commitments tend to induce brain drain effects because individuals covered by these commitments are usually those who have greater facility in acquiring permanent resident status or citizenship in the importing countries. 68 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific VI. Agriculture, Fisheries and Food Security Agriculture remains a mainstay of the Asian rural economy for incomes, employment, and nutrition and food security. Although its relative importance varies with countries, agriculture is a key sector in all countries, contributing to more than 25 percent of the GDP in South Asia and more than 15 percent in East Asia. More importantly, the majority of the Asian population \u2013 more than 57 percent \u2013 is employed in the agriculture sector. The disaggregated picture is even starker: In the poorest countries like Lao PDR and Nepal, the share of agriculture in GDP is more than 40 percent, while it employs around 80 percent of the labour force. In richer countries like Malaysia and Thailand, the GDP share of the sector is around 10 percent, but is still double the global average of 5 percent. It is evident that the degree of reliance on agriculture is quite systematically correlated with the depth of poverty. Thus, from the viewpoint of supporting livelihoods and empowering the poor in Asia \u2013 through incomes and employment \u2013 agriculture is paramount. Issues of nutrition and food security also are related to agriculture. Some 78 percent of malnourished children in the developing world live in Asia, and the FAO estimates that by 2010, Asia could be home to nearly 150 million malnourished children. From a human development perspective, malnutrition, hunger and poverty are unacceptable not only because they constrain people's capability to lead the kind of life they have reason to value and participate fully in socioeconomic activities, but widespread hunger also represents a morally unacceptable state in a world that has the knowledge and the resources to eradicate absolute poverty in", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "3dd6bbc7-ffa2-48e1-8222-6a3b1ce1806b": {"__data__": {"id_": "3dd6bbc7-ffa2-48e1-8222-6a3b1ce1806b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6f3da9eb1d99a0863dd33129a89d50559a0ddafcdbf291b62a9d0b5e06200f09"}}, "hash": "6f3da9eb1d99a0863dd33129a89d50559a0ddafcdbf291b62a9d0b5e06200f09", "text": "a generation. The incidence of hunger and poverty is high in areas characterised by weak agricultural production systems and absence of effective control by poor people of resources, such as land ownership and tenure, and access to credit, public infrastructure and markets. National policies recognise the importance of a reformed and productive 69 agriculture sector, and also their autonomous ability to shape domestic outcomes. A direct route to rural poverty alleviation is through increases in agricultural productivity and better food distribution systems. Asian governments recognise that investments in infrastructure, research and extension services and other incentives, promote agriculture and agro- industries to create new jobs and incomes. In all the countries we have studied, agriculture remains at the forefront of domestic policy. In Bangladesh, reforms have focused on rationalising tariffs, liberalising investment in irrigation and trade in fertilizers and equipment, and seed delivery. In India, the rural economy is dominated by small subsistence farmers; anti-poverty policies target them, but there is a need to reform the incentive regime that directs public funds to subsidise power, water and fertilizers, while crowding out investments in irrigation and other public works. In Malaysia, the dichotomous structure of subsistence farmers and large export-oriented plantations demands balancing of benefits of export incomes, with vulnerability to influx of subsidised imports. In Viet Nam, the doi moi reforms continue, and the role of the state remains important in stabilising prices and managing distribution and trade of commodities through STEs, especially in upland areas where the private sector has no incentive to operate. But as the country prepares to accede to the WTO, some of these policies will have to be defended forcefully in the accession negotiations. Because the role of the state in agriculture will continue to be crucial in many parts of Asia, these shifts will need to happen in a way that does not compromise the state's ability to meet its rural development obligations. Trade has increased the access of poorer countries to highly subsidised agricultural products from developed countries. This increased access holds the promise of improving health outcomes in poor countries and the capacity to smooth out domestic food supply disruptions. However, the actual pattern of liberalisation of trade in agriculture since the 1990s has seen the enormous opening of agricultural markets in developing countries and in new member countries of the WTO (including China), 70 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific unreciprocated by a comparable opening up in advanced country markets. First principles suggest that developing countries would have an in-built comparative advantage in international agricultural trade. When the pattern of liberalisation is heavily skewed against these countries, it closes the door of investment in these countries toward agricultural productivity increases and industrial processing of agricultural products. Developing countries also have more limited resources with which to subsidise their rural communities. Agricultural subsidies Agricultural subsidies Agricultural subsidies Agricultural subsidies Agricultural subsidies Subsidies by industrial nations to their agricultural outputs have depressed world prices and have often led to surges in imports, thereby undermining livelihoods and employment in the developing world. Unfair competition hurts legitimate exports from efficient, non- subsidised producers in developing countries. For instance, the heavy U.S.22 and EU support to their producers of edible oils has affected the prospects of Malaysia's most competitive and chief agricultural export earner, oil palm. Viet Namese prices for rice and green coffee beans also have declined sharply in recent years. Further, subsidy-driven overproduction has led to export dumping of products at prices lower than the cost of production. Dumping, however, is not only a North-South issue, but countries like Bangladesh also are equally wary of effects of neighbouring India flooding the regional market with subsidised reserves of rice and wheat. While cheap imports can be beneficial to poor countries in emergency situations, in developing Asian countries where 50 to 80 percent of the population are small or even subsistence farmers, the main concern is to 22 Bernardino (2005, p. 3) states that the United States, as the world\u2019s third-largest rice exporter, pays a subsidy of 72 percent of its cost of production. The study also indicates that, given the fact that production cost in the United States is more than twice the cost of the other two leading rice exporters, Thailand and Vietnam, a subsidy amount that high is not surprising. 71 provide higher income that will empower these people to move up out of poverty and create viable farm communities. Small producers also can be empowered through access to export markets. Low-cost agricultural imports, including food items dumped by rich countries, may affect long- term production patterns in countries", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4795090a-7a79-433a-b68c-2cbd7cecd547": {"__data__": {"id_": "4795090a-7a79-433a-b68c-2cbd7cecd547", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f4a62a48a9687bdcc37bcc979e3869b6ea98d672bc8cca38dfb7b10a625f4295"}}, "hash": "f4a62a48a9687bdcc37bcc979e3869b6ea98d672bc8cca38dfb7b10a625f4295", "text": "where agriculture meets an array of income, employment, food and cultural needs. Persistent trade deficits in food also undermine self-reliance in a strategic area and pose vulnerability issues during emergencies. Instead of undermining the livelihood of small farmers in developing countries with subsidised exports, advanced countries should support human development in developing countries by helping to create domestic productive capacities through technology and financial aid. Improvement in agricultural productivity is also dependent on labour productivity, so ODA should target investing in concerted public actions in education and training, health and nutrition, and infrastructure. Similarly, domestic support of various forms, either through market prices or fiscal handouts, also distorts production and trade. Agricultural subsidies have actually increased in the period since the Uruguay Round, and the recent U.S. Farm Act represents a major shift in the policies of the world's largest agricultural exporter towards greater subsidisation. While \"amber box\" type of support is faced with reduction commitments, developing countries have argued that \"blue\" and \"green\" box subsidies also should be disciplined.23 On a net basis, household incomes in developing countries are severely undermined by international agricultural trade flows because of imports of cheap agricultural commodities. International trade in goods produced from land also has spurred the production of cash crops, which are traded internationally, as opposed to food crops. This can provide additional sources of income for farmers and 23 See Dhar (2004, Section 6) for a discussion of various negotiating positions in reforming agricultural subsidies. 72 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific the ability to diversify their crops. Farmers shifting to cash crops accept the risk of losing a secure access to food, arising from the difference between the costs of providing food for their households and the income they receive from their cash crops. The WTO Agreement on Agriculture (AOA) should incorporate a \u201cDevelopment Box;\u201d indeed, developing countries have sought to expand the existing special and differential provisions in the AOA to cover broader issues of interest to them by proposing such measures. These proposals deal with all the three pillars of the AOA \u2013 market access, domestic support and export subsidies. Because the right to food is inalienable, and food security is a major non-trade24 concern, developing countries propose that food security crops (special products) should be exempt from significant tariff reduction commitments. What determines a \u201cspecial product,\u201d and how many of them should be listed, are a matter of negotiation. 24 The right to adequate food must have a priority over all other rights. It is a basic human right, a life and death issue. Without enough food, human development and, beyond that, human survival fails. Trade policies recognising the concept of the right to food and food security would definitely help protect people from hunger, help eliminating poverty. The content of a right to adequate food is elaborated upon by the United Nations Committee on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights, in a 1999 reading of the International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights. There, it is stated that the right is realised \u201cwhen every man, woman and child, alone or in community with others, (has) physical and economic access at all times to adequate food or means for its procurement \u2026. availability of food in a quantity and (of a) quality sufficient to satisfy the dietary needs of individuals, free from adverse substances, and acceptable within a given culture \u2026. accessibility of such food in ways that are sustainable and that do not interfere with the enjoyment of other human rights.\u201d All these imply that the right to adequate food surpasses responsibility on states to respect, protect and fulfill this right similar to all other social and economic rights. This means that, as stated by an International Food Policy Research Institute report, states should not adopt measures that could ultimately prevent access to adequate food, that they should adopt measures to ensure that no individuals are deprived of their access to adequate food, and that they should proactively engage in activities to strengthen people\u2019s access to and use of resources, including means to ensure their livelihood and food security (IFPRI, 2004, p.2). 73 Similarly, flexible provision of special safeguards (SSG), now only available to 39 WTO members, to counter surges in the volume or prices of imports through tariffs or quantitative restrictions, must be available for developing countries to protect vulnerable populations. Developing countries also propose to subject export credit and food aid (which the United States uses) to the same discipline as export subsidies (which the EU uses). Because rich countries have merely attempted to realign domestic support from areas", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "15d9817f-a823-4490-9bdc-55de3d2c7663": {"__data__": {"id_": "15d9817f-a823-4490-9bdc-55de3d2c7663", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fe40492902f71f389c7ce744c09557b67fda805bb2b87538e306ae49767df375"}}, "hash": "fe40492902f71f389c7ce744c09557b67fda805bb2b87538e306ae49767df375", "text": "obliging reduction commitment (amber box) to those not subject to reduction commitments (blue and green boxes), countries have proposed that so-called minimally trade-distorting forms of domestic support also should be brought under the AOA discipline. They further support stronger special and differential provisions that exclude support given to low-income farmers from calculation of aggregate measures of support (AMS), as well as payments to maintain domestic production capacity of staple crops for food security and viability of rural communities. Both are important human development objectives. Fisheries and sanitary standards Fisheries and sanitary standards Fisheries and sanitary standards Fisheries and sanitary standards Fisheries and sanitary standards Fishing contributes to empowerment by being a major source of food, employment and incomes and a way of life. Asian countries produce more than half of the world's fish. The fisheries sector offers employment to more than 25 million people, and exports account for nearly a quarter of the global volume. In developing countries in Asia, most of the fishing communities are small-scale (80 percent), with fishing mostly in coastal areas and using small fishing vessels of less than 5 gross tonnes. Many less developed Asian countries do not have major distant-water fleets, and their fisheries sector is not heavily commercialised. Most vessels lack communication, buoy and navigational security facilities; most are powered with small-capacity engines; and fishing is usually near-shore with traveling time and catches limited by the size of vessels. Most small-scale fishermen thus engage in day-to-day fishing, usually working as share-owners in nearby waters and relying on borrowed 74 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific financing. Small-scale fishing contributes to an equitable distribution of resources while being a source of food and casual employment. Most do not own their own boats and instead work as crew. Many poor fishers also do not have access to agricultural land, credit and capital equipment, and the open seas offer an opportunity to the marginalised. Resource depletion as a result of commercial exploitation has hit the poor hardest. Productive fish exporters are successfully competing in world markets. Fisheries and aquaculture are both growing export-oriented sectors in parts of Asia, bringing in an increasing share of GNP. Export of shrimp is growing the fastest, and the linking of aquaculture to export markets has encouraged diversification of exportable species and a shift from generalised fishing to targeting of key species. Viet Nam's export of aquatic products exceeded US$2 billion in 2002, up by nearly 45 percent from 2000. In India, export of frozen shrimp accounts for more than 60 percent of total fisheries export receipts, surpassing US$1.2 billion; seafood is considered the most important primary product export, earning almost 3 percent of foreign exchange. In Thailand, fisheries bring in close to US$ 5 billion annually, which is 4 percent of its GDP. Global trade barriers and practices severely constrain market access opportunities. The average tariff on fish products in major markets (relatively higher in the EU and China than the United States and Japan) is not significantly higher than the average of 6 percent for manufactured products, but certain products face peak rates and tariff escalation hinders export of processed fish products. Highly strict sanitary and environmental concerns act as a non-tariff barrier. Sanitary and environmental issues that appear alternately as food safety, as well as eco-labeling requirements, have acted as non-tariff barriers. EU, for example, has adopted a policy of \"zero tolerance\" to fish products containing residual antibiotics chloramphenicol (CAP). The recasting of sanitary standards to take advantage of more powerful measuring instruments has effectively raised sanitary standards against fisheries exports from developing countries, without recourse to scientific justification for such increases in standards. The standard set has been 75 strict enough to lead to a radical plummeting of shrimp exports to the EU from major Asian exporters like India and Thailand, affecting the livelihoods of thousands. 76 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific VII. Access to Basic Services Women\u2019s and men\u2019s livelihoods and the prospects of the next generation are directly affected by the household\u2019s access to education, health, water, energy and other services. Trade in services has become a key arena of international trade negotiation. The aim of these negotiations is to remove barriers to the supply of these services across national boundaries. In almost all cases, international provision involves the participation of international companies in these sectors. The gains from trade \u2013 of increased supply at higher quality \u2013 are the key potential benefits of these liberalisation efforts. For example, a rigorous econometric study found that in Argentina \u2013 where 30 percent of the municipality water systems were privatised", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e80c3314-72ed-4140-b70f-e72ccc9c693a": {"__data__": {"id_": "e80c3314-72ed-4140-b70f-e72ccc9c693a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "59e1a4ba351f636c1226ae6e36aed87c9107d4ebf6bc31808c954075a0fbb46b"}}, "hash": "59e1a4ba351f636c1226ae6e36aed87c9107d4ebf6bc31808c954075a0fbb46b", "text": "between 1991 and 1999, covering 60 percent of the population \u2013 the privatisation of water services has been associated with decreased child mortality rates of 5 to 7 percent (Galani et al. 2002). There is a wide variety of what would be deemed barriers to international provision of services \u2013 from visa requirements, to regulatory requirements, to ownership limits. Within the overall framework of liberalisation, countries negotiate to reduce these barriers in a reciprocal manner, even though it is clear that the most immediate commercial beneficiaries are based in the industrial economies. The services liberalisation effort is not directed at changing the public- private sector mix in the economy. However, developing countries tend to be characterised by the small size of their modern private sector, so that in these countries most of these services, which require a certain level of organisational and industrial capability, are publicly provisioned. A major concern of developing countries is the increased pressure to open up sectors that provide public goods and are currently Government-owned monopolies, such as water and energy services. While economists criticise many of these monopolies for inefficiency and for contributing to the budget deficit, there is concern that if public 77 goods are privatized, they will become more expensive and less accessible. Privatisation while aiming at efficiency could simply exacerbate the unequal distribution of income, which is a common characteristic in many developing countries. In India, for example, the Government started to privatise water but was forced to roll it back in response to protests (Center for International Environmental Law, 2002). Except for increased supply, and abstracting from deficiencies in distribution, the recent record of efforts to privatise key services, such as water, has not been exemplary. Private provision has tended to raise prices (although a certain proportion of these services are in the nature of public goods) even as private providers have found it difficult to collect from consumers and to cover their costs. Similar to trade liberalisation, services liberalisation has diverse gender impacts. Critiques of privatisation of basic services have point out that access to these services is limited to those who are able to pay (i.e., poor people, particularly poor women, who are not able to pay their bills face cutoffs in services). But the fact that women are the ones who usually substitute for the Governments\u2019 role in providing clean water, health care or education to children and the nursing of elderly people \u2013 i.e., the care economy \u2013 compensates for the absence of state social services. The private provision of clean drinking water, sanitation and other basic services must be regulated to address the health aspects of these services. Estimates reported in UNDP, RBF et al. (2003, p. 321) suggest that 3 million people, most of whom are children younger than 5, die annually in developing countries because of water-related diseases. In considering educational services, the imposition of user fees even at minimal levels frequently causes girls leave their schools first (Fosse 2001, p. 3). In a few well-publicized cases, private providers have been forced to withdraw because of the demonstrated commercial unviability of the project. 78 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific International provision, and with the proper regulatory regime, can certainly assist countries in providing their citizens access to high- quality services, such as advanced training and education. Beyond the public goods aspects of the provision of these services, there are issues of the \u201cpublicness\u201d of the nature of many these goods, such as the transmission of citizenship responsibilities and culture through education for the young. Governments need to carefully consider these issues as they decide which specific obstacles to increased trade in services should be removed. Access to energy services Access to energy services Access to energy services Access to energy services Access to energy services Access to clean and reliable sources of energy is crucial for human development. Despite declining real costs, the lack of access to energy not only undermines the productivity of an estimated one-third of the world's people, but it also causes insecurity and hardship and often threatens health and future well-being, while exacerbating inequalities. More than 2 billion people rely almost completely on traditional energy sources. The health of women and the education of children are particularly affected. Any policy to promote human development must effectively address this challenge. Many developing countries in Asia have been opening up their energy service sectors to foreign investment and participation, but have entered into little commitment in the GATS. Such liberalisation has been aimed at enhancing exploration efforts, increasing production, improving transportation of energy and increasing efficiency at", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8c97a4d3-7bda-47ec-961c-e6b7f0361af5": {"__data__": {"id_": "8c97a4d3-7bda-47ec-961c-e6b7f0361af5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d822abdbf9d2880c98359642b2fcb3966abb749684a5aada434e19d6c73ca501"}}, "hash": "d822abdbf9d2880c98359642b2fcb3966abb749684a5aada434e19d6c73ca501", "text": "all levels, especially the distribution of energy in the form of electricity and gas. Seen from a human development perspective, access to cheaper, more efficient energy will enhance the productivity of people and enable them to compete in a globalised world. However, such liberalisation implies that Governments will no longer be able to apply direct measures in the energy sector in support of human development goals, but will have to pursue these goals through new regulatory structures and actions on private enterprises. 79 Liberalisation cannot by itself satisfy the other components of human development. The increased efficiency does not only not benefit those many poor who are off the grid, but it also leads to higher prices, which aggravates the plight of the poor and even creates more poor, through the downsizing of employment. Without compensatory measures and conditions on foreign investors, involving transfer of technology requirements, social obligations, and prohibition of anti-competitive practices, liberalisation can undermine rather than promote human development, particularly by exacerbating existing inequalities. In GATS terms, this means introducing appropriate conditions into the GATS commitments to ensure the Governments' policy space to introduce and, if necessary, adapt and amend such regulation so that any gains from liberalisation are passed on to poorer people, including those who do not have access to energy networks. Health services Health services Health services Health services Health services Health services represent a critical component of human development. The provision of health services is directly affected by trade policy through two channels: (1) the liberalisation of trade in services and (2) the hardening of the international regime on intellectual property rights. Thailand has notably taken advantage of opportunities to provide health services to foreigners traveling to Thailand for health procedures. Another mode is for the entry of foreign health providers and that of health insurance providers into developing countries. As in the case of other services, countries need to define the proper limits on the privatisation of these services, which invariably happens with increased provision by foreigners. Permitting foreign health insurance providers to participate in the domestic provision of health services often involves an implicit decision to de-emphasise the technical and least-cost supply-side aspects, as opposed to the financing and demand-side control of the sector (Mackintosh 2003). A simple example is that in many basic aspects of health provision, universal provision, as opposed to targeted provision, is in many instances, the least-cost option. Basic health services are not only a human right, but they also are a public good, and attaining public 80 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific health objectives could be endangered if recast on a purely commercial basis. The inclusion of intellectual property protections within the disciplines of the WTO and bilateral trade agreements has raised global concerns about access to affordable medicines (Third World Network, 2003). Patent protection for pharmaceutical products and processes potentially can reduce competition from the generic production of medicines. All WTO members must adopt and enforce high standards of intellectual property rights protection, similar to the standards applied in developed countries. Combined with reduced state participation and regulation of health services, intellectual property protection has been known to lead to high prices, restricted access to medicines and the demise of domestic pharmaceutical production in developing countries. Moreover, because of heavy reliance on reverse engineering which patent protection makes illegal, domestic manufacturing of pharmaceutical products in developing countries could come to a halt. The multinational drug companies in about 10 countries own or control most of the pharmaceutical technologies and products through patents (Third World Network 2003). The 20-year patent protection required by the WTO TRIPS Agreement bestows upon a pharmaceutical company a monopoly over the production, marketing and pricing of patented medicines. No generic equivalent can come into the market until after 20 years. Protected against competition, drug companies can keep the price of the drug high during the protection period. In January 2005, the Indian Parliament updated its patent laws. The new system is intended to assist Indian pharmaceutical companies to protect their own inventions and align Indian law to the country's WTO commitments. The law tightens control over the production of generic versions of patented drugs. Because India is an important supplier to developing countries of antiretroviral drugs, these new rules will raise the cost of HIV/AIDS treatments worldwide. 81 The indirect channel through which trade policies affect health and other services is through their impact on fiscal resources. Trade liberalisation reduces tariff revenues, which is normally an easier revenue source to collect for poorer countries; the shrinking of total resources forces the state to choose priorities and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1dc60e95-83b0-4af5-9d34-a92e19a5e1c1": {"__data__": {"id_": "1dc60e95-83b0-4af5-9d34-a92e19a5e1c1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "67110b9e51bf11416cf44d9651c10603b3d17b152a842a7150ead4672939f361"}}, "hash": "67110b9e51bf11416cf44d9651c10603b3d17b152a842a7150ead4672939f361", "text": "in many cases, those services whose constituencies are the poor, such as public health, are cut. The expenditure side of the fiscal system also is affected by trade policies: Efforts at trade facilitation have cost implications. Changes in the cost of drugs, and the cost of enforcement of patent regimes, can have significant impact on the level of Government expenditures. In all, Asian countries are fierce trading nations. Because services are now inevitably subject to trade negotiations and disciplines, it would be in the interest of Asian countries to explicitly take into account trade developments in the design and planning of their social programmes. More importantly, Asian countries need now to incorporate social considerations into their trade policy and trade negotiations to take advantage of international opportunities and safeguard against the negative impacts of the burgeoning trade in services. 82 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific VIII. Social Resources for Investment Economic development is a social process. It requires an often extended (and in some highly successful countries, a concentrated) period of self- reinforcing investment in capital goods and skill-building, frequently at the expense of current consumption. Individual investors have to be willing to risk their resources in untested ventures, and Governments have to advance resources based on a calculated expectation of a private response. Investment is a social process because investment involves risk taking by a variety of independent actors in new activities whose return is uncertain, particularly in case of small domestic markets. There self- fulfilling optimistic expectations play a significant role in the behaviour of individual investors. Shifting demand from consumption to investment even by a single investor may lead to a \u201cbig push\u201d effect from a coordinated simultaneous investment by other individuals (Murphy et al. 1989, pp. 1004-1006). There is a big role for the state here, which requires an institutional capability to coordinate simultaneous attempts at investment across different sectors. Murphy et al. (1989) demonstrate theoretically how a single firm\u2019s investment decision, even though not profitable on its own, may attract other firms to do so and fosters a mutually profitable big-push impact in an economy. Successful Asian countries have managed this social process relatively well, often with institutional arrangements that would be considered primitive by Western standards. Successful countries also have managed the process of sequencing of reforms as the complexity of investment decisions increased. In the early stages of the process, Asian Governments have not only successfully used development banks but also have often controlled the whole financial sector for extended periods to ensure the availability of long-term investment funds beyond the short-term trade financing from commercial banks. During its 30-year success period just before the Asian crisis, Indonesia had an elaborate 83 selective credit allocation system that was the subject of constant criticism by Western economists. In fact, a large part of the speculative inflows that ultimately undermined the Indonesian banking system, and prepared the ground for its financial crisis, rushed in after the dismantling of these credit limits (Abdusalamov and Montes 1998). Having abandoned this system, the Indonesian Government could not reinstate limits on real estate investment and other speculative projects as foreign funds flowed into Asia in the mid-1990s. As in Thailand, domestic banks responded to their newfound external resources by rapidly bring into their portfolio more speculative projects. The implicit model underlying current thinking and policymaking with regard to liberalisation is that one gathers up a savings pool first and then allocates such a pool to projects that generate the best returns on the margin. A key motivation for the frantic rush with which non-member countries have sought to join the World Trade Organization has often been to send a signal to the world (where presumably an enormous pool of investible funds lies waiting to be tapped) and thereby motivate international investors. Often the existing structure of the trade and domestic production of candidate countries does not warrant a dash to join a body devoted to trade liberalization rather than investment promotion. Preparing an economy for hospitality to foreign investment generates significant demands on public resources that, at low levels of development, might have been invested instead in basic services at greater social return. The actual global experience in the last 15 years with regard to foreign investment flows is that this rush to join is unrequited. First, most of the global pool is invested in industrial economies and, second, of the funds that are invested in developing countries, at most five countries have benefited. Table 11 shows the breakdown of FDI flows by host region since the 1970s. Figures clearly indicate that more than", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cdd4e24c-c9ff-429d-a44b-397dfa61f387": {"__data__": {"id_": "cdd4e24c-c9ff-429d-a44b-397dfa61f387", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6da2b03100688120abb2ed9bc6475db724608e69fee2039abe304440c4702261"}, "3": {"node_id": "7d8dfbe7-a840-4433-aeed-cfb00f91fa30", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "69232fc2460ec7952bc460d979225b54723ffd5f1a5a928cc601d15d05c1dfe6"}}, "hash": "ee36cfc2315088d14ace92518388e9b67c8221680614cb7e9ae36e4ec2910052", "text": "70 percent (except in the 84 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific 1990s, where the figure is 66 percent) of world FDI is destined for the developed countries. Except for Asia and Southest Europe with CIS countries, in all developing regions there is a downward trend. In Africa, it declines from 5 percent to 2 percent between the 1970s and 1990s, while in Latin America and the Caribbean, it decreases to 10 percent from 13 percent. When we look at the breakdown among sub-regions within Asia, we see diverse patterns again. While East Asia increases its share in world FDI inflows from 2 percent (1970s) to 11 percent (1990s), Southeast Asia\u2019s share decreased almost by 50 percent. On the other hand, West Asia\u2019s share exhibits only a slight rise from 0.6 percent to 1 percent. During most of the recent period, most foreign investment arrived in Asia through China, and during most of the same period, China was not a member of the WTO. Table 12 sustains evidence for this observation. In considering the list of top 10 countries, since the 1990s China has become No. 2, getting the highest share of FDI inflows in the world. China replaced the United Kingdom\u2019s position in the 1970s as well as the 1980s. For the whole period, the United States has been getting the highest share among all destinations. Except for Brazil (1970s and 1980s), Mexico (1980s and 1990s) and China as mentioned, no other developing country joins the developed countries in the top 10 lists. Beyond this, the figures in the bottom row in Table 12 speak for themselves. The total of the shares of the top 10 countries, though lower in the first four years of 2000s (75 percent), stood at more than 93 percent from the 1970s to the 1990s (and in the 1980s ran as high as 99 percent).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7d8dfbe7-a840-4433-aee