rtakes the role of accumulating productive capital (Lipietz 1998). Developing a domestic private sector Developing a domestic private sector Developing a domestic private sector Developing a domestic private sector Developing a domestic private sector The Asian experience has proven the critical role of a vibrant private sector. In the most recent important case, China, the emergence of new private production activities \u2013 even if nominally owned by state organs \u2013 is a key reason why foreign investors have found the country an attractive investment destination. The aphorism that foreigners would not invest in a country in which residents themselves are not investing applies. What is the role of state in helping to nurture a domestic private sector? The answer surely depends on the level of development and the historically inherited capabilities of the state and the local private sector. In countries that have been successful in overcoming underdevelopment, a domestic private sector was nurtured, whether by conscious policy (in many cases driven by appeals to nationalism) or as an almost unintended outcome of the political process. Trade policy has been a key aspect in the building up of a domestic private sector. Countries that are now industrialised, during their development phase, had industrial tariffs that were far higher than the current tariffs in developing countries or LDCs. The United States had average applied tariffs of 40 to 50 percent for much of the century from 1820 to 1920. In comparison, the average rate in 2001 in developing countries as a whole was 8.1 percent and in LDCs 13.6 percent (Aky\u00fcz 2005). State interventions in the trade regime create enormous advantages, in the form of profits above free-market levels to favoured elements of the private sector. These \u201crents,\u201d if not properly managed, can become entitlements and undermine entrepreneurial energies, with adverse consequences for productivity growth (Chang 1994, p. 42-43 and p. 83). Rents can be applied to political contests, taking the form of 88 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific consumption expenditures as opposed to being reinvested, in order to protect these advantages (Montes 1995). Rents also can be poorly reinvested.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "003c0d90-728a-421b-9343-36948964f232": {"__data__": {"id_": "003c0d90-728a-421b-9343-36948964f232", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "092f99e8c46ac0ddbe466d3c55ec296f746ea985f5df2f50c187a52c45d5e676"}, "2": {"node_id": "03a8dd66-b9bc-40bc-9d28-fa286fc243b7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "938cc87f3a52fe68992a6d93973b8950d64080278f969113408328939dd70e21"}}, "hash": "8ad02b04d30d966add1587b2b7b6903ff59d05cbcaff2a18c0aba5188570569f", "text": "Rents also can be poorly reinvested. There is no doubt that enormous advantages handed out through a heavily politicised trade policy process have been subject to abuse both historically and in the post-World War II period, when many developing countries undertook import substitution. Trade policy reforms in the 1980s and 1990s have been mainly motivated politically by arguments to cast out abuses and corruption, and partly by a", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5ea4ed1c-e3a6-4cea-9a37-ad077806d63c": {"__data__": {"id_": "5ea4ed1c-e3a6-4cea-9a37-ad077806d63c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "896023f9fcd544eb6778fc4a0730d9ea653deff10ad98491ab6aa7a4b1de6150"}, "3": {"node_id": "b8dda1b7-27fa-4947-99ba-82cf6598b826", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "776f7ee239f94dc4f4a973622c37ad126ed4348e020fe4c5b678a6d83549433f"}}, "hash": "42fdd69fa7f2d2bfd144b2f463b6da22bf1b577b03bd7ee371844e4f03878634", "text": "new implanted hope on the part of developing country officials to rely on foreign investment. There is equally no dearth of corruption to accompany foreign investment projects to the benefit of developing country officials; this has, in turn, sparked demands to deregulate foreign investment entry. Why is the existence of a domestic private sector critical to development? It is critical because the permanent impact of development is in the increase in capabilities and productivity of an economy. This private, individual capacity has to be embodied somewhere. A domestic private sector, operating in areas beyond retail marketing, is the site where increases in national productivity can be rooted. Corruption and political abuse need to be addressed without sacrificing the existence of a sector where human productivity can be developed and permanently located. Economies that have insufficient locations of this type will tend to see their citizens seeking productive employment in foreign countries. Developing Asia-Pacific countries need to preserve their policy space for assisting their domestic private sector, even as international negotiations intensify to restrict such space. Bilateral and regional trade agreements Bilateral and regional trade agreements Bilateral and regional trade agreements Bilateral and regional trade agreements Bilateral and regional trade agreements At Doha (2001) it was agreed that \"recognizing the case for a multilateral framework to secure transparent, stable and predictable conditions for long-term cross-border investment, particularly foreign direct investment \u2026 negotiation will take place after the 5th session of the 89 Ministerial Conference on the basis of a decision to be taken, by explicit consensus, at that Session on modalities of negotiations.\" At the Fifth Ministerial Conference in Cancun, because of the successful resistance on the part of developing countries, further negotiations in the WTO on an investment treaty were terminated. However, investment restrictions have expanded enormously in bilateral and regional investment treaties. Although not a new phenomenon, since the establishment of the WTO and its \u201cSingle Undertaking,\u201d the number of Regional Trade Agreements (RTAs) has increased dramatically25. Many of new waves of RTAs also extend beyond tariff liberalisation to include more intrusive obligations, especially on intellectual property rights, services and investment. The process is further complicated by the fact that traditionally RTAs were concluded among bordering countries with comparable levels of development, while the new wave of regionalism involves diverse countries located in different time zones26. The failure of the Cancun Ministerial Conference to move the multilateral negotiating process forward has intensified interest in bilateral and regional options for expansion of trade relations. Many developing countries have sought to partner with richer, Northern countries, reciprocating preferential access to their markets with similar concessions in different sectors. However, as RTAs tend to involve the freeing of \"substantially all\" trade and normally contain \"WTO-plus\" obligations, their impact on human development can be pronounced. Indeed, the RTAs seem to magnify the scope and intrusiveness of policy restraints and liberalisation commitments already covered under WTO obligations. The benefits arising from improved access to markets have to 25 \u201cAs of January 2005, 312 RTAs have been notified to WTO/GATT (of these, 170 are in force) and a further 65 are estimated to be operational although not yet notified\u201d (Crawford et Al., 2005, p.2-3). 26 \u201cSwimming in the Spaghetti Bowl: Challenges for Developing Countries under the New Regionalism,\u201d Luis Abugattas Majluf, UNCTAD, 2004. 90 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific be weighed against reciprocal concessions made elsewhere, in terms of their combined impact on human development and livelihood prospects of poor citizens. A recent WTO discussion paper on RTAs argues that because RTAs are becoming increasingly complex, complicated rules of origin likewise makes trade more costly and complex. The study also argues that unless RTA rules are not accompanied by a concurrent multilateral system, they may jeopardise a balanced development of world trade. Elevated trade and investment diversion would marginalise the \u201cweakest\u201d countries (Crawford et al. 2005, p.16). This view supports earlier findings by Bhagwati and Panagariya (1996) and Venables (1999) where the former demonstrates that the growing significance of trade diversion (i.e., the rise in trade among RTA members at the expense of trade between RTA members and others) diverts trade from non-members and least-cost suppliers. This is likely to reduce welfare not only in outsiders but also in member countries.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b8dda1b7-27fa-4947-99ba-82cf6598b826": {"__data__": {"id_": "b8dda1b7-27fa-4947-99ba-82cf6598b826", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "896023f9fcd544eb6778fc4a0730d9ea653deff10ad98491ab6aa7a4b1de6150"}, "2": {"node_id": "5ea4ed1c-e3a6-4cea-9a37-ad077806d63c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "42fdd69fa7f2d2bfd144b2f463b6da22bf1b577b03bd7ee371844e4f03878634"}}, "hash": "776f7ee239f94dc4f4a973622c37ad126ed4348e020fe4c5b678a6d83549433f", "text": "This is likely to reduce welfare not only in outsiders but also in member countries. The latter argues that RTAs, if formed among low- income countries, are likely to harm the lowest income member, with losses attributable to trade diversion; unless there is at least one high- income member, convergence to a high-income level is not possible (Venables 1999, p. 20). The counter-argument of Blomstr\u00f6m and Kokko (1997) relies on the diverse impacts of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "0c8fb1f9-2e22-4b5c-b713-3ad918a9f12e": {"__data__": {"id_": "0c8fb1f9-2e22-4b5c-b713-3ad918a9f12e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "992f624c8574a4150a9bb73ccf2528d0a13f303926f828516248e8b6c1677053"}, "3": {"node_id": "dd5dfd28-8e95-4b63-b1f2-cc0a39aec7f2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bbff05689c1a3426a837fbab00969c06c13482dab78213ccafc6b24e9ce1d22e"}}, "hash": "593c5f0421c7fab3fdf4b58225a364bc83b7b449c22e824666666fb69521e56c", "text": "RTAs on investments in general, particularly on FDI. RTAs affect FDI flows through two channels: First, there are indirect effects through trade liberalisation; second, effects occur through changes in investment rules imposed within RTAs. How RTAs affect FDI depends on the total magnitude of these two effects (Blomstrom and Kokko 1997, p. 2-3). The study basically points out the fact that RTAs raise the potential for investment, as a result of a bigger market size. On evaluating the diverse implications on different member countries of MERCOSUR (Blomstrom and Kokko 1997, p. 29-30), they suggest additional provisions in RTAs to facilitate FDI. Other possible benefits of RTAs, from an investment point of view, are discussed in other studies as 91 well. Fernandez (1997, p. 27) states that RTAs might provide certainty and credibility as to the future policies and economic environment, which can increase private investment. By reducing uncertainties via commitment, signaling and insurance mechanisms, RTAs might serve to increase credibility and provide benefits to member economies. RTAs also have potential impacts on productivity and growth. Schiff et al. (2002) finds that both North-South and South-South research and development flows have a positive impact on total factor productivity. The study argues that RTAs are likely to favour the development of low- resesarch and development-intensity industries in the South and might retard the economic transformation of member countries to a high- research and development economy by reducing technology spillovers from the North (Schiff et al. 2002, p. 16). This result can be interpreted to imply that RTAs are good for growth, unless trade is limited within member countries. In other words, unless countries are locked into trading only with each other, then the potential for higher research and development flows leads to higher growth. RTAs might provide an environment for the members to sponsor their research and development expenditures jointly and form regional research and development clusters in the region. Because uncertainty matters much in research and development expenditures, why not share the risks or the benefits at the end? Another aspect is the welfare impact of RTAs, which also involve their political dimension. Schiff and Winters (1997, p. 29) argue that RTAs, as diplomacy, unambiguously increase welfare, given the condition that it reduces security tensions and conflict. However, Brown et al. (2005) take a contrary view, arguing that regional cooperation is no panacea for regional conflict (Brown et al. 2005, p. 14). RTAs cannot be taken as an automatic brake on conflict. In fact, regional integration, according to the authors, can actually create tensions and trigger conflict by creating adjustment costs, social dislocation and a widening of wealth inequalities. Trade diversion and exclusion can create tensions between members and non-members of trade agreements.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dd5dfd28-8e95-4b63-b1f2-cc0a39aec7f2": {"__data__": {"id_": "dd5dfd28-8e95-4b63-b1f2-cc0a39aec7f2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "