: "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "126d579895180aacf15ec08ad40d3b692b1eb265e6af3bbab4731cdfa201e55d"}}, "hash": "fea688b03979aa9459e9c8e85520be97de79e1c1dd34c9f3028289058ad29d87", "text": "4.9 4.9 4.9 4.9 4.9 MERCOSUR N/A 14.5 18.1 N/A 8.9 8.9 20.5 N/A 10.7 14.0 21.3 23.0 Andean Community N/A 6.4 12.6 12.0 N/A 4.1 11.8 11.9 N/A 7.9 12.3 11.4 ASEAN 13.2 14.6 16.9 20.9 17.2 18.2 23.4 19.8 15.2 16.3 20.0 20.3 EU (15) 57.3 65.9 62.4 61.8 52.9 63.2 61.0 59.4 55.0 64.5 61.7 60.6 Source: Source: Source: Source: Source: Pitigala (2005, p. 8), Table 2 93 Given these general theoretical arguments, it will be necessary to undertake more research on case-specific issues in Asia. The basic argument is that, if properly designed, B/RTAs are likely to provide opportunities for developing countries to extend human development capabilities, while avoiding possible drawbacks from trade liberalisation. In Asia, countries have been involved in regional integration for many years, including the regional system of tariff preferences, the Bangkok Agreement, and sub-regional processes like SAFTA and AFTA. Recently there has been intensification of efforts to deepen such ties through negotiation of bilateral FTAs, including within the framework of agreements between sub-regional groupings. China has become active in negotiating such FTAs, and countries like Japan, which have been historically aloof to RTAs, are reinvigorating their efforts. Asian countries also are negotiating FTAs with countries outside the region. Questions thus arise on how these new integration arrangements promote trade and development as well as benefit and impact on the poorer sections of society \u2013 and indeed, whether they are compatible to the letter and spirit of the multilateral trading system. South Asia is a sub-region where there has been a recent surge in interest in regional trading agreements; recent research indicates changes in the pattern of intra-regional trade in South Asia. Pitigala (2005, p. 8) provides a review of intra-regional trade shares in total trade in selected years from 1981 to 1998; Table 13 below is adapted from this study. The significant impacts of RTAs in the region also can be observed from figures in Table 13. In aggregate, South Asian intra-regional trade doubled in eight years (from 2.4 percent in 1990 to 4.9 percent in 1998). The figures first imply that the significance of intra-regional trade increased in all member countries while also reflecting the increased economic growth rates recently experienced in the sub-region. Second, compared to other sub-regions, South Asia\u2019s performance is very low in 94 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific absolute terms27, but when we look at the impacts in each country, we observe that figures for Bhutan (from 10 percent to 72 percent) and Nepal (12 percent to 33 percent) demonstrate significant increases. Given the fact that these two countries are landlocked, this change might not be surprising, yet such a large increase would not be achieved without agreements with India. Thus, RTAs have the potential to expand trade opportunities for landlocked countries. The differing bargaining power and capabilities stemming from asymmetric political and economic strengths of nations are well-known drawbacks of regional trade agreements. Intra-regional import shares in Bangladesh, Maldives and Sri Lanka rise more than the export shares. One underlying reason, Pitigala (2005, p. 9) argues, is the imbalance as a consequence of India\u2019s maintaining a higher level of border protection relative to its neighbours. Such imbalances also may reflect dynamic effects generated by the differential level of export diversification among trading partners. India and Pakistan are cited as the only countries exporting a wide range of manufactured goods from automobiles to medicine, whereas other countries\u2019 exports are usually concentrated in a single sector, such as beans, rice or apparel28. The new wave also presents Asian countries with the opportunity to tailor their own bilateral and regional standards.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7505c260-fd56-4aeb-b45a-511a702955a1": {"__data__": {"id_": "7505c260-fd56-4aeb-b45a-511a702955a1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "b2fd123436e0fcceab58eeecf237916ba7b0fffc84d9b670d9128098aadcf4be"}, "2": {"node_id": "8782c53f-7dcc-4084-9ecc-9b8cf43cbf2f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fea688b03979aa9459e9c8e85520be97de79e1c1dd34c9f3028289058ad29d87"}}, "hash": "126d579895180aacf15ec08ad40d3b692b1eb265e6af3bbab4731cdfa201e55d", "text": "The new wave also presents Asian countries with the opportunity to tailor their own bilateral and regional standards. Developed countries appear to be using FTAs to pursue commitments in areas such as 27 The reasons behind this relative poor performance are argued as follows: First, South Asian countries are not \u201cnatural trading partners,\u201d i.e., this is a hypothesis that states that a successful regional agreement requires disproportionate trade among members; second, export goods in the region are not complementary except exports of Pakistan and India; third, beyond these, the majority of export goods are textile and clothing products, where they compete each other; and fourth, recent bilateral agreements with industrialised countries shifted exports from intra-regional trade to outside the region, such as that of Bangladesh and Sri Lanka (Pitigala (2005, p.42-43)) 28 See Pitigala (2005, p.22) for more details. 95 investment and labour rights, which have been kept off the multilateral agenda. The Bilateral Investment Treaties (BITs) that some developing countries are signing with the United States, Canada and Japan include restricted use of investment measures permitted under the WTO. FTAs", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f341fdff-a6fe-49bb-9970-239153d3a315": {"__data__": {"id_": "f341fdff-a6fe-49bb-9970-239153d3a315", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d8cd0e3f0dd3ce531dea81af82abef102ee2377a0a09bf876aae991834a429e3"}}, "hash": "d8cd0e3f0dd3ce531dea81af82abef102ee2377a0a09bf876aae991834a429e3", "text": "are usually WTO-plus in terms of their sectoral coverage, definition and dispute settlement provisions, and provide improved access to markets for goods and services. Some regional blocs include facilities for Movement of Natural Persons; ASEAN countries, for instance, are devising a framework that will encourage greater mobility of labour across borders by simplifying visa and licensing procedures, and promoting recognition of qualifications. Similarly, in sectors like agriculture, fisheries, and textiles and clothing, B/RTAs could offer improved market access, but in return for conditions and restrictions on national policies whose development merits are yet to be assessed. Agriculture agreements could require limited use of safeguard measures; fisheries could include ecolabeling and prevention of depletion of stocks; textiles and apparel could involve outward processing arrangements and other rules of origin that would inhibit textile trade among Asian countries, even undermining the competitiveness of the exporting country. FTAs and BTAs also could contain higher standards for intellectual property that exceed the minimum levels of protection that TRIPS mandates for patents, copyrights, trademarks and geographical indicators, possibly having an impact on sensitive issues of public health and technology transfer. Unless care is taken in the legal definitions, the danger also exists that nationals of countries other than those directly involved in the agreement would inadvertently benefit (and perhaps evade regulatory requirements) through subsidiaries incorporated in the parties involved. In considering the FTA option, particularly with developed countries outside the region, Asian countries must take into account that free trade in sectors of interest to them might in any case be achieved through the zero-for-zero formula in the Doha Round. The negotiation of FTAs 96 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific appears to emerge from a different domestic political dynamic than those underlying multilateral rounds. At the same time, the use of FTAs by certain major powers to obtain strategic political objectives departs from the basic principle of the GATT/WTO system, which has always sought to depoliticise trade relations (Van Grasstek 2003). Based on a variety of recent experiences in negotiating RTAs, developing countries of this region need an effective and sophisticated strategy to avoid the dangers and exploit the opportunities in these kinds of agreements. Investment measures Investment measures Investment measures Investment measures Investment measures Many domestic investment measures have clear human development objectives that can be undermined by new multilateral disciplines. Proposed multilateral investment agreements tend to prohibit or restrict many investment policy measures currently available to developing countries. Such measures include the screening of entry of investment, limitations of control and ownership, performance requirements (e.g., transfer of technology, export performance, employment), and investment incentives. The real question is whether it is in the interest of Asian developing countries to accept such constraints that eliminate or restrict their use of specific investment measures currently at their disposal. Many investment measures that are targeted for restriction or prohibition would seem to have been conceived with clear human development goals in mind, such as protecting the environment, promoting the interests of disadvantaged social and ethnic groups, reducing gender and regional inequalities, providing stable and improved employment opportunities, enhancing skills and access to technologies, and facilitating access to world markets. For example, measures that seek to limit foreign ownership and control empower people to have more control over vital economic decisions that can affect their lives. Investment measures such as labour rights and employment performance requirements, property rights, pro-competition measures, social accountability of trans-national 97 corporations, and cultural exceptions are also central to empowerment. Other investment measures are aimed at promoting equitable access to opportunities, correcting for regional, ethnic and gender inequalities. These include regional and sectoral incentives and investment incentives for SMEs; employment- and gender-related performance requirements; and universal and public service requirements. In addition, other investment measures are aimed at ensuring a sustainable future through environmental requirements, expropriation law, investment safeguards, balance-of-payments requirements, and restrictions on short-term capital flow. Quite a few Asian countries have been vociferous opponents of incorporating multilateral obligations on investment into the WTO system. Some opposition even comes from countries that have been seen to have greatly benefited from FDI, and which are currently primary destinations for FDI. The idea that foreigners could exercise property rights in the hosting countries through the threat of trade sanctions has generated much political heat in these countries. Successful Asian experiences suggest that rapid development has been achieved through strategies that depend primarily on domestic investment. Foreign investment played a critical role in achieving specific goals as part of an overall strategy (Amsden and Chu 2003). The specific goals included rapid employment absorption, industrial \u201cupgrading,\u201d balance-of- payments contribution, technology transfer,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b42330ce-dd51-4b01-8913-3a358ad4efe7": {"__data__": {"id_": "b42330ce-dd51-4b01-8913-3a358ad4efe7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "113c536693ca1b583bae5fe67df6ad92374a82e2dd0ca1e90b950d1b108bdfd6"}}, "hash": "113c536693ca1b583bae5fe67df6ad92374a82e2dd0ca1e90b950d1b108bdfd6", "text": "securing of raw materials supply, capturing of new foreign markets, and access to credit and brands of foreign investors. Such an overall strategy sought to strengthen the regulatory capacity of the host Government to ensure that foreign enterprises operations aligned with national goals. Industrial tariffs and industrial policy Industrial tariffs and industrial policy Industrial tariffs and industrial policy Industrial tariffs and industrial policy Industrial tariffs and industrial policy Another means by which successful Asian societies historically mobilised resources for investment, mostly paid for by domestic consumers, is through the system of industrial tariffs and quantitative restrictions on 98 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific imports. For efficiency and governance considerations, quantitative restrictions are now mostly applied to \u201csensitive\u201d products. Developing countries need the flexibility to set tariffs and change them as the level of development changes, in order to encourage investment in specific sectors of the economy. For example, labour-surplus countries could use tariffs to encourage labour-intensive manufactures and reduce these tariffs when wages increase. Aky\u00fcz (2005) warns that the more prominent proposals in the ongoing negotiations at the World Trade Organization on Non-Agricultural Market Access (NAMA) will banish this flexibility. These proposals have the potential implication of binding tariffs on a line-by-line basis that would be irreversible and have raised concerns about the viability of domestic investment in developing countries. In these proposals, developing countries are being asked, in effect, to cut their tariffs much more rapidly than the developed countries had done in the 30 years after the Second World War. 99 IX. Technological Upgrading and Innovation Innovation and the upgrading of the technical capacity embodied in produced goods has been a critical element of the Asia\u2019s success in securing productivity and wage growth and the sustainability of its participation in world markets. Successful Asian countries started off at low levels of technical capability. The interaction with the international economy provided these countries with the understanding of what would be required to upgrade production. International trade was used to import capital equipment and to purchase foreign technology. Successful countries also have regulated international investment to ensure that technology would be transferred to domestic users (Amsden 2001). In the case of the Republic of Korea, there was a specific bias against depending on foreign investment to gain access to foreign technology; instead, the state assisted private companies in acquiring foreign technology (Cassen and Lall 1996; Chang 1994), organising consortia to purchase technology and assisting in identifying which technologies to purchase. The Singaporean approach has depended more heavily on foreign investment, but even here, as the economy attempts to adapt more complicated technology, the state has set up companies to undertake research and development. A significant element of the learning from foreign direct investment that has benefited host economies derives from skill upgrading, through training of workers and their operational experience in actual production activities. Technical advances are often embodied in modifications and adaptations of plants and equipment (Lall 1998). The spread of knowledge has been more effective in countries where the national innovation system is structured to facilitate absorption. Developing economies cannot rely on foreign firms to undertake research and development in their own countries. The experience of Singapore, Ireland and Israel suggests that interventionist policies are required to 100 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific ensure that research and development activities migrate from only production-related activities to applied research and development (Rasiah 2003). \u201cThere is convincing evidence that regulation on ownership conditions cannot simply be viewed to be inversely correlated with technological capability building. There is little evidence to suggest that foreign firms will relocate substantial innovation-related activities in developing economies, even in economies considered to offer equal treatment to local and foreign firms\u201d (Rasiah 2003, p. 9-10). The establishment of an international regime that would secure the transfer of technology has been a key demand of developing countries since the formation of the GATT. Recent developments, such as the absorption of intellectual property rights in the trade regime and restrictions on trade-related investment measures, have diminished the ability of national authorities to embark on technological upgrading and have increased their dependence on foreign firms for access to technology. 101 X. Conclusion For the countries of this region, the key issue is whether trade will continue to play a positive role in human development, as it did in successful East Asian countries. The East Asian model relied on a strategic role of the state in managing external trade; are international rules governing trade disallowing elements of this approach by unduly fettering state capacity? This model depended upon modernisation of the domestic private", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6709bb8b-f2ba-455e-bdfe-ecd8d6b62f8a": {"__data__": {"id_": "6709bb8b-f2ba-455e-bdfe-ecd8d6b62f8a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "af4c9b458efdbede0054962c47dd98576046463bdda26968b8f0f41cc4187ad3"}}, "hash": "af4c9b458efdbede0054962c47dd98576046463bdda26968b8f0f41cc4187ad3", "text": "sector in order to achieve permanent improvements in international competitiveness; are current trade disciplines forcing domestic enterprises to face foreign competition prematurely, and not permitting them a grace period in which to build up their capacity to compete? The East Asian model, starting as it did from a relatively more egalitarian distribution of wealth, was characterised by relatively equitable growth, so that workers captured part of their productivity growth in their own income. Is the prevailing model dependent on the progressive fraying of the social fabric, underpinning an economy\u2019s international competitiveness from the sustainability of low wages and vulnerable employment? The key messages of the Asian experience are the following: The key messages of the Asian experience are the following: The key messages of the Asian experience are the following: The key messages of the Asian experience are the following: The key messages of the Asian experience are the following: Asian countries have demonstrated that trade and foreign investment can be mobilised to achieve human development. This has been achieved through a strategic, as opposed to a passive, approach to international integration. A passive approach, which relies heavily on low wages and cheaper raw materials, can condemn economies to their given place in the international division of production. An active, strategic approach consciously undertakes policies to drive a country\u2019s production activities toward higher levels of productivity, value-addition and higher wages. In the successful Asian cases, the record also is that human development has been critical in sustaining the growth process. These countries were able to secure a virtuous cycle between international economic integration and human development. The Asian countries have shown the possibility that, instead of international economic integration being a force for 102 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific social disintegration, external trade and investment can lead to higher levels of social well-being and achievement. In Asia\u2019s successful exploitation of trade for development purposes, social intervention, primarily through state policies but also through partnerships with the private sector, has played a key role. Creating a domestic labour force and a private sector that, while initially requiring protection and state assistance, can compete internationally has been a key Asian approach. Successful countries in the region demonstrate that a robust domestic economy is indispensable to a productive and strategic integration with the global economy. Yet changes in international trade rules are proscribing many of the trade strategies that Asian countries used to achieve human development (UNDP, RBF, et al. 2003, p. 66). The policy space of developing countries is much more restricted than that which the currently developed countries (Chang 2002), or the early Asian industrialisers had (Chang and Green 2003). Flexibilities in regard to tariffs and investment regulation, which were critical to the Asian story, are being eroded. Even as there are potential benefits from foreign provision, trade rules are interfering with social responsibilities to ensure access to basic services by citizens of developing countries. Asian countries thus should integrate trade and social policy. Recent developments, particularly the elimination of textile quotas, represent a challenge to Asia\u2019s export-oriented integration with the global economy and will inflict significant job losses on some countries, while other countries in the region benefit. A set of approaches exists that countries should undertake to mitigate the negative impact and take advantage of the opportunities from the changes in international rules. First and foremost, LDCs should be afforded preferential access to external markets to ease their transition. Asian countries need to seize the opportunity of the quota elimination as an occasion to diversify their production trade structures away from overdependence on the textile 103 and clothing sectors. Asia is playing host to the next high point in trade negotiations: the WTO Ministerial meeting in Hong Kong in December 2005. This meeting takes place in the first year in which the quota system of textile and clothing ended. The Hong Kong meeting should be the occasion to realize the commitment of the Doha Ministerial Declaration, which required Special and Differential Treatment for LDCs to become \u201cmore precise, effective and operational.\u201d What is at stake in the current trade negotiations, both in the WTO and in other bilateral and regional arenas, is nothing less than the ability of Asian countries to pursue their human development commitments under the Millennium Development Goals and the aspirations of their own populations. 104 | People, Trade and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific References Abdusalamov, Muhammad Ali and Manuel F. Montes (1998) \u201cIndonesia: Reaping the Market\u201d in Jomo K.S (ed.), Tigers in Trouble: Financial Governance, Liberalisation and Crises in East Asia (London: Zed Books Ltd.), pp. 162-180. Aky\u00fcz, Y\u00e9lmaz (1999)", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e661d67a-3210-4c9a-b90f-946471796891": {"__data__": {"id_": "e661d67a-3210-4c9a-b90f-946471796891", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "People, Trade, and Development: Learning from Asia-Pacific", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c94f8468a749fc379b8820273b8bb1117f9806767bf9db97d6bafd05c4b3bc0c"}, "3": {"node_id": "f3e2f156-23ed-4626-93f1-3d318e7ccd91", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/people-trade-and-development-learning-asia-pacific", "Author": "United Nations Development Progr