s Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1bc1957f564416e04414f75436d8e290aa2ad9669ce0a62f832446a69115e263"}}, "hash": "3e01102d25fe1e6a80451add05e5f446694529f782c5dc230de2ad8896137698", "text": "Conclusion 56 8.1 Looking ahead 56 References 58 Annex 1 : Schedules of developing Asian countries 62 List of tables Table 1 : Share in world commercial services trade by region, 2005 (in percentage) 11 Table 2 : Change in share of services output in countries of Asia (expressed as a percentage of GDP) 12 Table 3 : Change in value of exports and imports of services 13 Table 4 : WTO members in Asia with dates of membership 14 v About Asia Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative In recent years international trade has assumed a central role in economic growth and poverty reduction efforts in developing countries. Accordingly, the Asia Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative (APTII) of the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) Regional Centre for Asia Pacific, Colombo Office has been working to develop new approaches and strategies designed to help align trade dynamics with the objectives of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b4537527-50fa-407c-9b53-a6a0db5b8849": {"__data__": {"id_": "b4537527-50fa-407c-9b53-a6a0db5b8849", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "91b37bd1ab172dfe8f1ea89fdbd6e4f94b5ae0ef39a9ac3d6407476f96acc4c3"}, "3": {"node_id": "765c2c8c-5864-4ed4-b678-2bd95552d856", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c7bd882841faed174bfca39f543bf224f1f8d14a1f43d10a600b93eb3c2899c2"}}, "hash": "db54d17e03c5c4bbe27bd5012977ea9b552e08c836540983e4c6fdc1b935ad7b", "text": "poverty reduction and human development in the Asia Pacific region. Since its founding in 2002, the APTII has promoted innovative research and policy advice that seeks to define clear substantive linkages between trade and human development, and that is consistent with the objective of supporting the Millennium De- velopment Goals (MDGs). The APTII, striving to build on its previous work and achievements in this third and current phase of its work programme (2008-2011), aspires to make a significant contribution to policy dialogues by fostering re- gional trade and investment regimes that are consistent with human development goals in the region. A cen- tral challenge facing policy-makers is to facilitate patterns of inclusive regional integration that enable them to address specific development priorities and goals, particularly with reference to the development needs of least developed countries (LDCs), landlocked developing countries (LLDCs), and small island developing states (SIDS). The focus of APTII\u2019s current work programme, therefore, is on: 1) enhancing trade competitive- ness and capacity development to formulate employment-responsive and gender-responsive trade policies; and 2) strengthening the capacity to implement pro-poor regional integration strategies, including through key regional processes and/or mechanisms. In line with this focus, APTII will publish a series of studies and discussion papers highlighting the policy implications of the multifaceted dimensions of current trade trends and patterns, as well as their human development impact in the Asia Pacific region. vi Preface With the spread and deepening of the global financial crisis across the world, a number of issues are likely to be intensely debated in the coming months and years. Policy makers in the Asia Pacific region for instance need to think creatively about national, regional and global policy options addressing the inherent vulnerabilities in the region arising on account of the current nature and pattern of production and international trade in goods and services. Equally, the realization seems to be hitting home that a strategic approach to trade and investment liberalization efforts under the General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS) is a critical ingredi- ent for resilience and prevention of the worst effects of boom-bust cycles across economies in the region. The APTII study on Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences, highlights inter alia that there is a case for countries to adopt a calibrated approach to liberalization of GATS investment rules to harness development benefits. The Study brings out the various dimensions of policy space in the context of GATS and juxtaposes select Asian experiences on liberalization of investment rules. It argues that given the differences in stages of development and policy imperatives, it would be important for countries to both preserve and leverage the GATS flexibilities as the negotiations unfold in the future. Unbridled liberaliza- tion of the services, sector without a robust, credible and effective regulatory framework relevant especially for financial services needs to be revisited as a lesson learnt of the current economic crisis. The global crisis reminiscent of the Great Depression of the late nineteen twenties and thirties, is a signal call for countries to rethink the critical issues of regulation before liberalization and, as a response policy makers need to leverage and retain flexibilities and safeguards in services negotiation at the bilateral, regional and global levels. It is our hope that this policy paper will prove useful to governments, UNDP country offices, research institutions, civil society organizations and other stakeholders in the Asia Pacific region in furthering the debate on services liberalization with a human development orientation. Omar Noman Chief of Policies and Programmes UNDP Regional Centre for Asia Pacific Colombo Office vii This paper was written under contract with the Asia Pacific Trade and Investment Initiative, UNDP Regional Centre for Asia Pacific, Colombo Office. The authors wish to thank K.M. Gopakumar for providing invaluable inputs on this paper as a peer reviewer as well as Ratnakar Adhikari, Bryn Gay, Cecilia Oh, Swarnim Wagle, Cha- trini Weeratunge, Yumiko Yamamoto and members of the Knowledge Resources Committee, UNDP Regional Centre for Asia Pacific, Colombo Office, for their substantive comments. Professional editing by Prabhash Ranjan is gratefully acknowledged. Additional editing by Chatrini Weeratunge is deeply appreciated. Editorial assistance provided by Randika Jayasinghe is noted with gratitude.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "765c2c8c-5864-4ed4-b678-2bd95552d856": {"__data__": {"id_": "765c2c8c-5864-4ed4-b678-2bd95552d856", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "