 "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f45233bb5c6b22f25a0308e758fe0d59edcaadbcdcd923df60934ef5de84cc3a"}}, "hash": "f45233bb5c6b22f25a0308e758fe0d59edcaadbcdcd923df60934ef5de84cc3a", "text": "Trade in Services GATT General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade GDP Gross Domestic Product HKMT Hong Kong Ministerial Text ISPs Internet Service Providers JV Joint Venture KT Korea Telecom LDCs Least Developed Countries MA Market Access M&As Mergers and Acquisitions MAI Multilateral Agreement on Investments MFN Most Favoured Nation NACs Newly Acceded Countries NHAI National Highway Authority of India NT National Treatment ODI Overseas Development Institute OECD Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development PPPs Public Private Partnerships PTCL Pakistan Telecommunication Company Limited QFII Qualified Foreign Institutional Investor QRs Quantitative Restrictions R&D Research and Development RBI Reserve Bank of India TPR Trade Policy Review TRIMs Trade Related Investment Measures UNCTAD United Nations Conference on Trade and Development US/USA United States/ United States of America VSAT Very Small Aperture Terminal WIR World Investment Report WLL Wireless Local Loop WTO World Trade Organization Abbreviations and acronyms ix The services sector has emerged as a strategic contributor to the growth of gross domestic product (GDP) across the Asian economies, and is expected to provide an inclusive character to this growth. Governments in the region understand the need to utilize the growing contribution of the service sector as a site to generate employment opportunities, but are challenged with issues of liberalization of services, either autonomously or at bilateral, regional and multilateral levels. Attempts at liberalization of services are fraught with debates of how commitments at the said levels constrain the policy space of governments to regulate services for achieving objectives of human develop- ment. Policy space in this context is a reference to the scope for domestic policies of a government, especially in the areas of trade, investment and industrial development which is often framed by international disciplines, commitments and global market considerations. The rapidly expanding range and scope of trade policies at the bilateral, regional and international levels have critically impinged upon the availability and exercise of \u2018policy space\u2019 in developing countries in several interlinked ways. There is concern for how governments in Asia, especially those of Newly Acceding Countries (NACs), are utilizing the existing policy space under the General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS) to schedule their commitments. This paper seeks to focus attention on the commitments made to the World Trade Organization (WTO) by select Asian countries, including some NACs, to liberalize investment flows across different service sectors through commercial presence in the territory of a Member State (Mode 3), in view of the unique relevance of these commitments from a policy space and human development perspective. \uf06c The study of GATS commitments made brings to light diverse approaches in utilising the flexibilities under the GATS architecture and undertaking liberalisation commitments. In general, the approaches seem to be based upon the stage of development of the services sector and tailoring to local needs and priorities in individual cases. Although the Study finds no readily discernable consistent pattern, the flexibility does permit an economic powerhouse like China to utilize the GATS framework to signal a level of restraint when opening key sectors (like banking), while permitting a country like Nepal to keep itself unbound for a series of financial services until the groundwork for opening up is prepared. \uf06c Overall, commitments made by selected countries at an autonomous level are often deeper, in com- parison to the commitments undertaken by them under GATS on the same set of services. This may be taken as indicative of the existence and utilization of appropriate space and flexibility for contextualising developmental policies to local needs and priorities. Executive summary x \uf06c Preliminary research suggests that the NACs may have been subject to greater pressures for liberalization of investment rules. There is a concern that most of the NACs have not taken recourse to the flexibilities embedded in the GATS architecture to schedule limitations even in sectors such as health, education and environment which are critical from the point of view of human development and therefore needing appropriate government regulation prior to liberalization commitments. In some instances, the sectors appear to have been opened up without the benefit of adequate experiences in setting up or maturing of the regulatory institutions. This has implications for policy space to operationalize developmental goals. It needs to be emphasized that in practice, reversal of the GATS commitments is virtually impos- sible without incurring significant and possibly unacceptable costs by the countries wishing to change the same under the existing WTO framework. Accordingly, in general, it would be preferable to adopt a cautious approach rather than locking oneself into binding commitments into the future especially on the question of provision of essential services. While liberalization offers opportunities for increased", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "80c157da-2cbc-415e-a074-e4747c9bf7b2": {"__data__": {"id_": "80c157da-2cbc-415e-a074-e4747c9bf7b2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6b8b88155aec69bd0e9b3e4dfbc6d4c692952c4aa3ca9bc977586e498286bb5b"}, "3": {"node_id": "dd37b5a1-5a85-4a13-b9c3-066ce44d6126", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9af85d4387920a8ba1f10cc8acea41fc6249debdde29786c5a57358178f3dae0"}}, "hash": "f3cfda97027d19453977fd7ed9dc5ad786509a2c8e0f0d08df2ee7ca791edbab", "text": "economic growth and development, an un- regulated liberalization process can potentially undermine development goals such as universal access to es- sential services especially for countries where the vast majority of the poor depend greatly on public goods. 1 Services are the fastest growing sector of the world economy constituting nearly two thirds of global output, one third of global employment and nearly 20% of global trade.1 With some qualifications, this is especially true for Asia where unprecedented rates of growth have been led and accompanied by a significant increase in the economic importance of the services sector. For most countries including some least developed countries (LDCs)2, the services sector is now the biggest contributor to gross domestic product (GDP) and considered in- strumental in employment generation and enhancing human development outcomes.3 An efficient services sector, given its cross sector and economy-wide efficiency linkage is considered a prerequisite for attainment of international competitiveness and economic growth. The growing importance of the services sector has led some to argue that there are substantial gains from freeing up trade in services either autonomously or through bilateral, regional and multilateral chan- nels. Others have suggested a calibrated approach after due factoring in of costs and benefits. As is known, the General Agreement on Trade in Services (GATS) sets forth the first ever set of multilateral disciplines for international trade in services. It has an inbuilt agenda of progressive liberalization (Article XIX) wherein Members enter into successive rounds of negotiations not later than five years from the date of entry into force of the World Trade Organization (WTO) agreement. Negotiations in the services sector are ongoing in the Doha Round as well. The WTO\u2019s services sectoral list classifies services in 12 broad categories and includes education, health-related and social services, financial services, research and development, communication, retailing and transport services amongst others.4 Trade liberalization of the services sector covers practically all the services with limited exceptions. Again, trade in services is categorized to be carried through four different modes of supply as defined in Article I of the GATS.5 The rationale for the Study arises from the wide scope and breadth of the services sector targeted for liberalization and its potential impact on the ability of governments to tailor domestic policies for trade and investment while respecting international commitments and considering global markets. Such room for maneuver within the framework of multilateral commitments is also referred to as \u2018policy space\u2019. Policy space is continually challenged in the process of conforming to agreements like GATS for example, through the requirement that each Member State has to take necessary steps to ensure that regional, local and non- governmental bodies within its territory observe the commitments made. This often renders ineffectual their ability to pursue development goals. 1. Introduction 1 http://www.wto.org/english/thewto_e/whatis_e/tif_e/agrm6_e.htm 2 Nielson and Taglioni (2004). 3 UNCTAD (2005). 4 Services Sectoral Classification List, MTN.GNS/W/120, World Trade Organisation, available at http://www.wto.org/english/tratop_e/serv_e/ serv_e.htm 5 The concept of different modes of supply in the GATS has been discussed in Chapter 3. Policy space. 2 It needs to be appreciated that liberalization in services trade is fundamentally different and more complex than liberalization in goods trade. Simply put, while the latter primarily involve measures \u2018at the border\u2019, the former encompasses regulatory and government policy issues, or what are typically termed \u2018behind the border measures\u2019. Services trade liberalization, therefore, has multiple linkages and a much wider policy ambit and associated developmental impacts which are important to be factored in any liberalization episode. A focus on policy space implications for the current liberalization episodes in the services sector vis-\u00e0-vis the flexibilities which exist in the GATS is thus topical and relevant. The scope and coverage of GATS to include services supply side Mode 3 (through commercial presence in the territory of any other Member) has often been seen as an indirect attempt to set in place multilateral rules for investment on services in the light of previous failures on this count. Service supply through Mode 1 (cross-border movement of services) and Mode 4 (cross border movement of natural persons) are often linked to commercial presence and add to the economic importance of Mode 3.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dd37b5a1-5a85-4a13-b9c3-066ce44d6126": {"__data__": {"id_": "dd37b5a1-5a85-4a13-b9c3-066ce44d6126", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6b8b88155aec69bd0e9b3e4dfbc6d4c692952c4aa3ca9bc977586e498286bb5b"}, "2": {"node_id": "80c157da-2cbc-415e-a074-e4747c9bf7b2", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f3cfda97027d19453977fd7ed9dc5ad786509a2c8e0f0d08df2ee7ca791edbab"}}, "hash": "9af85d4387920a8ba1f10cc8acea41fc6249debdde29786c5a57358178f3dae0", "text": "The list of multinational service providers eager to tap into the potential efficiencies of a developing country market has also been increasing over the past few years and such countries face mounting pressure to deliver on their international commitments to liberalize. It may be recalled that international rules governing foreign direct investment were sought to be introduced amongst the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) countries in 1998 in the form of a Multilateral Agreement on", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9a26fef0-dd7c-40f2-8a14-fd0650e5a328": {"__data__": {"id_": "9a26fef0-dd7c-40f2-8a14-fd0650e5a328", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2170aed5c26a4074f266330a907858e1081396d020958b2a56dd1258210e144c"}}, "hash": "2170aed5c26a4074f266330a907858e1081396d020958b2a56dd1258210e144c", "text": "Investments (MAI), but did not succeed. A key apprehension aris- ing on account of MAI was that the agreement would undermine the sovereign ability of governments to regulate investments to suit diverse development objectives. A similar attempt to include investments on to the agenda of the WTO was resisted strongly by the developing countries. Although the Agreement on Trade Related Investment Measures (TRIMs) was agreed to in the WTO to address the trade restrictive and distorting effects of investment measures, it is restricted to trade in goods and fell short of a comprehensive WTO regime for investments.6 However, the GATS agreement in effect has been seen as creating an additional window for liberalizing further investment flows via Mode 3 and place a scaled down version of a multilateral agreement on investments. The need for such an agreement especially from the point of view of the developed countries arises on account of the large flows of foreign direct investment (FDI) globally in the services sector. Cross border investment has been growing in magnitude and importance. FDI flows were in the order of US$ 1.2 trillion in 2006, with approximately US$ 325 billion going to developing countries.7 In terms of sectoral composition, half of the FDI flows went to the services sector in 20048, especially to banking, telecommunications and real estate; a trend facilitated by the process of liberalization and relaxation of foreign ownership requirements and privatization efforts whether driven autonomously or by the WTO.9 6 This theme has been discussed further in Chapter 3. Policy space. 7 World Bank (2007). 8 2004 is the most recent year for which the data on sectoral composition of FDI is available. 9 Ibid. 3 The objective of this Study is to focus attention on the liberalization commitments entered into by select Asian countries including by some Newly Acceding Countries (NACs) to the WTO in Mode 3 across different sectors. The context being that the liberalization of the services sector especially in Mode 3 has assumed a unique relevance from a policy space and human development perspective. In addition to making the analy- sis broader in scope, aside from the schedule of commitments entered into countries, revised offers10 of some countries and autonomous liberalization trends have also been incorporated into the analysis. Also, there are aspects of GATS which have raised questions about whether or not its implementa- tion would affect the ability of governments to provide and regulate essential services in the public interest. By way of illustration, health care, education and water and sanitation services, promotion of research and development, pursuit of balanced regional growth and the promotion of backward and forward linkages by prescribing local content requirements for industries with an influx of FDI and so on would be affected in myriad ways. These essential services are known to be underprovided in developing countries. Increased private sector participation is of limited help and value due to high costs which tends to exclude the poor and vulnerable and also poses a number of regulatory challenges.11 The issue of effective regulation in the services sector is critical since the \u2018production\u2019 and \u2018consumption\u2019 of services occurs simultaneously without any inter- vening opportunity to inspect, like in the case of goods. While GATS in principle does provide the flexibility of limiting the scope of liberalization commitments by scheduling limitations horizontally across sectors and by way of Most Favoured Nation (MFN) and National Treatment (NT) limitations and recognizes the rights of governments to regulate, a critical area of concern has been the actual practice in this regard: whether or not governments have in reality exercised and utilized the flexibilities embedded in the agreement and retained policy space to regulate effectively without fetters. Another issue of importance has been the question of opening up without a proper regulatory regime/apparatus in place and lack of previous experience in several areas which are new and evolving in nature. A push for liberalization in areas where a particular service sec- tor is yet to mature sans the regulatory framework is akin to putting the cart before the horse. The World Bank has documented how the process of financial liberalization which preceded a new legal and regulatory framework for prudent risk taking and market discipline \u2018led to a series of bank failures which caused losses to taxpayers and depositors equivalent to 7 percent of GDP in Zambia.\u2019 12 2. Objectives and approach 10 There are no documents available to research into the nature of \u2018requests\u2019 as governments are free to approach others bilaterally and there are no notification requirements within the WTO relating to \u2018requests\u2019. 11 See for details on", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7a2321e4-b973-45fa-9912-bfdca1312297": {"__data__": {"id_": "7a2321e4-b973-45fa-9912-bfdca1312297", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f6dc75faaf043c3b5ee9e541d120db306aa26c43bfb6be885e5848bb646a865c"}}, "hash": "f6dc75faaf043c3b5ee9e541d120db306aa26c43bfb6be885e5848bb646a865c", "text": "under provisioning of essential services in developing countries, Oxfam International (2006). \u201cIn the Public Interest: Health, Education and Water and Sanitation for All\u201d. Oxfam International and Water Aid Report, Oxford: Oxford International. 12 The Contribution of Services to Development and the Role of Trade Liberalisation and Regulation, ODI Briefing Notes, Dfid, UK, OECD Global Forum on International Investments, March 2008, available at www.oecd.org/dataoecd/54/1/40302909.pdf, accessed on April 24, 2008. 4 Studies of this nature delving into the commitments of countries which have been scheduled as well as those on offer with this perspective are useful for gaining new insights into the debate on policy space and providing inputs for informing services negotiations at the regional and multilateral levels in the future. The limitations of the Study however, need to be borne in mind. The scope of analysis of commitments is limited to Mode 3 and encompasses only select sectors/countries and is intended to offer a preliminary assessment. The Study does identify the need to undertake follow on country and sector specific research underpinned by data and information taking into account the experience of liberalization and challenges arising therein. Also, for most countries, documents on revised and updated offers in the ongoing negotiations continue to be restricted.13 Thus, as far as revised offers go, coverage is limited to countries where the revised offer docu- ments are available in the public domain. Lastly, data and information on the specific country context both in general and on the accession processes and dynamics have been obtained through desk research and often not sufficient to get a complete picture. 13 The study makes an attempt to review country schedules and autonomous commitments. 5 In a world characterized by different levels of development across countries and regions, the concept of policy space is seen as fundamental to the pursuit of development goals and in safeguarding the interests of developing countries in the international trading system. The need for policy space is well established on both theoretical and empirical counts. In many developing countries market failures are seen to persist, thereby providing a firm rationale for state intervention and regulation. Also, the East Asian development experiences and successes have demonstrated the utility of a state facilitated development policy approach.14 Despite this, it has been seen that the availability of policy space with developing countries has been shrink- ing steadily and rendered ineffectual so much so that their ability to pursue development goals itself has now been constrained. This has been especially so in the area of trade and industrial policies.15 Thus, for instance, some research findings suggest that more than 25 percent of all the WTO dispute settlement cases brought forth between 1995 and 2005 have in effect served to dismantle the policy space of developing countries.16 In the trading arena, the rapidly expanding range and scope of trade policies at the bilateral, regional and international levels have critically impinged upon the availability and exercise of policy space to devel- oping countries in several interlinked ways. For one, trade policy now encompasses rule making and new disciplines over and beyond the traditional areas covered under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) such as agriculture, services, intellectual property and investment. This implies a qualitative change for developing countries as rule making now involves domestic regulatory and legal systems which are embedded in the institutional infrastructure of the economy at national and sub-national levels having a wide ambit.17 For example, Article I. 3 (a) of the GATS stipulates that scope of the agreement encompasses measures taken by central, regional or local governments and authorities in a delegated capacity. Further, it mentions that in fulfilling its obligations and commitments under GATS, each Member is required to take such reasonable measures as may be available to it to ensure their observance by regional and local govern- ments and authorities and non-governmental bodies within its territory.18 Also, harmonization of rules and 3. Policy space 14 See UNCTAD (2007). Reclaiming Policy Space: Domestic Resource Mobilization and Developmental States. New York and Geneva: UNCTAD. Chapter 3 discusses the nature and relevance of the concept of policy space. The report notes for instance, \u201cContrary to popular perception, advocating the use of government policy to correct some of the egregious excesses of the market is not tantamount to a return to statism or protectionist economic policies. Rather, it is a call to move away from preoccupations with policies based on the ideological divide of \u201claissez faire\u201d and \u201cdirigisme\u201d to a set of more refined and eclectic policy measures that combine features of both, but tailored to the specific development challenges or circumstances of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2f98dfe4-e411-49a1-bfd3-98f8f3867928": {"__data__": {"id_": "2f98dfe4-e411-49a1-bfd3-98f8f3867928", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Policy Space and Investment Rules under GATS: Select Asian Experiences", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/policy-space-and-investment-rules-under-gats-select-asian-experiences", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United N